  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-1>1</A> Introduction</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>This document describes an extension to the HTTP/1.1 protocol that =
allows=20
  clients to perform remote web content authoring operations. This =
extension=20
  provides a coherent set of methods, headers, request entity body =
formats, and=20
  response entity body formats that provide operations for:=20
  <P>Properties: The ability to create, remove, and query information =
about Web=20
  pages, such as their authors, creation dates, etc. Also, the ability =
to link=20
  pages of any media type to related pages.=20
  <P>Collections: The ability to create sets of documents and to =
retrieve a=20
  hierarchical membership listing (like a directory listing in a file =
system).=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-6>Page 6</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>Locking: The ability to keep more than one person from working on a =

  document at the same time. This prevents the "lost update problem," in =
which=20
  modifications are lost as first one author then another writes changes =
without=20
  merging the other author's changes.=20
  <P>Namespace Operations: The ability to instruct the server to copy =
and move=20
  Web resources.=20
  <P>Requirements and rationale for these operations are described in a=20
  companion document, "Requirements for a Distributed Authoring and =
Versioning=20
  Protocol for the World Wide Web" [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2291.html">RFC2291</A>].=20
  <P>The sections below provide a detailed introduction to resource =
properties=20
  (section 4), collections of resources (section 5), and locking =
operations=20
  (section 6). These sections introduce the abstractions manipulated by =
the=20
  WebDAV-specific HTTP methods described in section 8, "HTTP Methods for =

  Distributed Authoring".=20
  <P>In HTTP/1.1, method parameter information was exclusively encoded =
in HTTP=20
  headers. Unlike HTTP/1.1, WebDAV encodes method parameter information =
either=20
  in an Extensible Markup Language (XML) [REC-XML] request entity body, =
or in an=20
  HTTP header. The use of XML to encode method parameters was motivated =
by the=20
  ability to add extra XML elements to existing structures, providing=20
  extensibility; and by XML's ability to encode information in ISO 10646 =

  character sets, providing internationalization support. As a rule of =
thumb,=20
  parameters are encoded in XML entity bodies when they have unbounded =
length,=20
  or when they may be shown to a human user and hence require encoding =
in an ISO=20
  10646 character set. Otherwise, parameters are encoded within HTTP =
headers.=20
  Section 9 describes the new HTTP headers used with WebDAV methods.=20
  <P>In addition to encoding method parameters, XML is used in WebDAV to =
encode=20
  the responses from methods, providing the extensibility and=20
  internationalization advantages of XML for method output, as well as =
input.=20
  <P>XML elements used in this specification are defined in section 12.=20
  <P>The XML namespace extension (Appendix 4) is also used in this =
specification=20
  in order to allow for new XML elements to be added without fear of =
colliding=20
  with other element names.=20
  <P>While the status codes provided by HTTP/1.1 are sufficient to =
describe most=20
  error conditions encountered by WebDAV methods, there are some errors =
that do=20
  not fall neatly into the existing categories. New status codes =
developed for=20
  the WebDAV methods are defined in section 10. Since some WebDAV =
methods may=20
  operate over many=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-7>Page 7</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>resources, the Multi-Status response has been introduced to return =
status=20
  information for multiple resources. The Multi-Status response is =
described in=20
  section 11.=20
  <P>WebDAV employs the property mechanism to store information about =
the=20
  current state of the resource. For example, when a lock is taken out =
on a=20
  resource, a lock information property describes the current state of =
the lock.=20
  Section 13 defines the properties used within the WebDAV =
specification.=20
  <P>Finishing off the specification are sections on what it means to be =

  compliant with this specification (section 15), on =
<BR>internationalization=20
  support (section 16), and on security (section 17).=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-2>2</A> Notational Conventions</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Since this document describes a set of extensions to the HTTP/1.1 =
protocol,=20
  the augmented BNF used herein to describe protocol elements is exactly =
the=20
  same as described in section 2.1 of [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2068.html">RFC2068</A>]. =
Since this=20
  augmented BNF uses the basic production rules provided in section 2.2 =
of [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2068.html">RFC2068</A>], =
these=20
  rules apply to this document as well.=20
  <P>The key words "<STRONG>MUST</STRONG>", "<STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG>", =

  "<STRONG>REQUIRED</STRONG>", "SHALL", "SHALL NOT", =
"<STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG>",=20
  <STRONG>SHOULD NOT</STRONG>", "<STRONG>RECOMMENDED</STRONG>",=20
  "<STRONG>MAY</STRONG>", and "<STRONG>OPTIONAL</STRONG>" in this =
document are=20
  to be interpreted as described in <A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2119.html">RFC 2119</A> =
[<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2119.html">RFC2119</A>].=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-3>3</A> Terminology</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>URI/URL - A Uniform Resource Identifier and Uniform Resource =
Locator,=20
  respectively. These terms (and the distinction between them) are =
defined in=20
  [<A =
href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2396.html">RFC2396</A>].=20
  <P>Collection - A resource that contains a set of URIs, termed member =
URIs,=20
  which identify member resources and meets the requirements in section =
5 of=20
  this specification.=20
  <P>Member URI - A URI which is a member of the set of URIs contained =
by a=20
  collection.=20
  <P>Internal Member URI - A Member URI that is immediately relative to =
the URI=20
  of the collection (the definition of immediately relative is given in =
section=20
  5.2).=20
  <P>Property - A name/value pair that contains descriptive information =
about a=20
  resource.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-8>Page 8</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>Live Property - A property whose semantics and syntax are enforced =
by the=20
  server. For example, the live "getcontentlength" property has its =
value, the=20
  length of the entity returned by a GET request, automatically =
calculated by=20
  the server.=20
  <P>Dead Property - A property whose semantics and syntax are not =
enforced by=20
  the server. The server only records the value of a dead property; the =
client=20
  is responsible for maintaining the consistency of the syntax and =
semantics of=20
  a dead property.=20
  <P>Null Resource - A resource which responds with a 404 (Not Found) to =
any=20
  HTTP/1.1 or DAV method except for PUT, MKCOL, OPTIONS and LOCK. A NULL =

  resource <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> appear as a member of its parent=20
  collection.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4>4</A> Data Model for Resource =
Properties</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.1>4.1</A> The Resource Property =
Model</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Properties are pieces of data that describe the state of a =
resource.=20
  Properties are data about data.=20
  <P>Properties are used in distributed authoring environments to =
provide for=20
  efficient discovery and management of resources. For example, a =
'subject'=20
  property might allow for the indexing of all resources by their =
subject, and=20
  an 'author' property might allow for the discovery of what authors =
have=20
  written which documents.=20
  <P>The DAV property model consists of name/value pairs. The name of a =
property=20
  identifies the property's syntax and semantics, and provides an =
address by=20
  which to refer to its syntax and semantics.=20
  <P>There are two categories of properties: "live" and "dead". A live =
property=20
  has its syntax and semantics enforced by the server. Live properties =
include=20
  cases where a) the value of a property is read- only, maintained by =
the=20
  server, and b) the value of the property is maintained by the client, =
but the=20
  server performs syntax checking on submitted values. All instances of =
a given=20
  live property <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> comply with the definition =
associated with=20
  that property name. A dead property has its syntax and semantics =
enforced by=20
  the client; the server merely records the value of the property =
verbatim.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.2>4.2</A> Existing Metadata =
Proposals</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Properties have long played an essential role in the maintenance of =
large=20
  document repositories, and many current proposals contain some notion =
of a=20
  property, or discuss web metadata more generally. These include PICS=20
  [REC-PICS], PICS-NG, XML, Web Collections, and several proposals on=20
  representing relationships within HTML. Work on PICS-NG=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-9>Page 9</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>and Web Collections has been subsumed by the Resource Description =
Framework=20
  (RDF) metadata activity of the World Wide Web Consortium. RDF consists =
of a=20
  network-based data model and an XML representation of that model.=20
  <P>Some proposals come from a digital library perspective. These =
include the=20
  Dublin Core [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2413.html">RFC2413</A>] =
metadata=20
  set and the Warwick Framework [WF], a container architecture for =
different=20
  metadata schemas. The literature includes many examples of metadata, =
including=20
  MARC [USMARC], a bibliographic metadata format, and a technical report =

  bibliographic format employed by the Dienst system [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc1807.html">RFC1807</A>].=20
  Additionally, the proceedings from the first IEEE Metadata conference =
describe=20
  many community-specific metadata sets.=20
  <P>Participants of the 1996 Metadata II Workshop in Warwick, UK [WF], =
noted=20
  that "new metadata sets will develop as the networked infrastructure =
matures"=20
  and "different communities will propose, design, and be responsible =
for=20
  different types of metadata." These observations can be corroborated =
by noting=20
  that many community- specific sets of metadata already exist, and =
there is=20
  significant motivation for the development of new forms of metadata as =
many=20
  communities increasingly make their data available in digital form, =
requiring=20
  a metadata format to assist data location and cataloging.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.3>4.3</A> Properties and HTTP =
Headers</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Properties already exist, in a limited sense, in HTTP message =
headers.=20
  However, in distributed authoring environments a relatively large =
number of=20
  properties are needed to describe the state of a resource, and=20
  setting/returning them all through HTTP headers is inefficient. Thus a =

  mechanism is needed which allows a principal to identify a set of =
properties=20
  in which the principal is interested and to set or retrieve just those =

  properties.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.4>4.4</A> Property Values</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The value of a property when expressed in XML <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> =
be well=20
  formed.=20
  <P>XML has been chosen because it is a flexible, self-describing, =
structured=20
  data format that supports rich schema definitions, and because of its =
support=20
  for multiple character sets. XML's self- describing nature allows any=20
  property's value to be extended by adding new elements. Older clients =
will not=20
  break when they encounter extensions because they will still have the =
data=20
  specified in the original schema and will ignore elements they do not=20
  understand. XML's support for multiple character sets allows any=20
  human-readable property to be encoded and read in a character set =
familiar to=20
  the user. XML's support for multiple human languages,=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-10>Page 10</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>using the "xml:lang" attribute, handles cases where the same =
character set=20
  is employed by multiple human languages.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.5>4.5</A> Property Names</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A property name is a universally unique identifier that is =
associated with=20
  a schema that provides information about the syntax and semantics of =
the=20
  property.=20
  <P>Because a property's name is universally unique, clients can depend =
upon=20
  consistent behavior for a particular property across multiple =
resources, on=20
  the same and across different servers, so long as that property is =
"live" on=20
  the resources in question, and the <BR>implementation of the live =
property is=20
  faithful to its definition.=20
  <P>The XML namespace mechanism, which is based on URIs [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2396.html">RFC2396</A>], =
is used to=20
  name properties because it prevents namespace collisions and provides =
for=20
  varying degrees of administrative control.=20
  <P>The property namespace is flat; that is, no hierarchy of properties =
is=20
  explicitly recognized. Thus, if a property A and a property A/B exist =
on a=20
  resource, there is no recognition of any relationship between the two=20
  properties. It is expected that a separate specification will =
eventually be=20
  produced which will address issues relating to hierarchical =
properties.=20
  <P>Finally, it is not possible to define the same property twice on a =
single=20
  resource, as this would cause a collision in the resource's property=20
  namespace.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.6>4.6</A> Media Independent Links</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Although HTML resources support links to other resources, the Web =
needs=20
  more general support for links between resources of any media type =
(media=20
  types are also known as MIME types, or content types). WebDAV provides =
such=20
  links. A WebDAV link is a special type of property value, formally =
defined in=20
  section 12.4, that allows typed connections to be established between=20
  resources of any media type. The property value consists of source and =

  destination Uniform Resource Identifiers (URIs); the property name =
identifies=20
  the link type.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-11>Page 11</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5>5</A> Collections of Web =
Resources</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>This section provides a description of a new type of Web resource, =
the=20
  collection, and discusses its interactions with the HTTP URL =
namespace. The=20
  purpose of a collection resource is to model collection-like objects =
(e.g.,=20
  file system directories) within a server's namespace.=20
  <P>All DAV compliant resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the HTTP =
URL=20
  namespace model specified herein.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.1>5.1</A> HTTP URL Namespace =
Model</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The HTTP URL namespace is a hierarchical namespace where the =
hierarchy is=20
  delimited with the "/" character.=20
  <P>An HTTP URL namespace is said to be consistent if it meets the =
following=20
  conditions: for every URL in the HTTP hierarchy there exists a =
collection that=20
  contains that URL as an internal member. The root, or top-level =
collection of=20
  the namespace under <BR>consideration is exempt from the previous =
rule.=20
  <P>Neither HTTP/1.1 nor WebDAV require that the entire HTTP URL =
namespace be=20
  consistent. However, certain WebDAV methods are prohibited from =
producing=20
  results that cause namespace <BR>inconsistencies.=20
  <P>Although implicit in [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2068.html">RFC2068</A>] =
and [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2396.html">RFC2396</A>], =
any=20
  resource, including collection resources, <STRONG>MAY</STRONG> be =
identified=20
  by more than one URI. For example, a resource could be identified by =
multiple=20
  HTTP URLs.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.2>5.2</A> Collection Resources</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A collection is a resource whose state consists of at least a list =
of=20
  internal member URIs and a set of properties, but which may have =
additional=20
  state such as entity bodies returned by GET. An internal member URI=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be immediately relative to a base URI of the =
collection.=20
  That is, the internal member URI is equal to a containing collection's =
URI=20
  plus an additional segment for non- collection resources, or =
additional=20
  segment plus trailing slash "/" for collection resources, where =
segment is=20
  defined in section 3.3 of [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2396.html">RFC2396</A>].=20
  <P>Any given internal member URI <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> only belong to =
the=20
  collection once, i.e., it is illegal to have multiple instances of the =
same=20
  URI in a collection. Properties defined on collections behave exactly =
as do=20
  properties on non-collection resources.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-12>Page 12</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>For all WebDAV compliant resources A and B, identified by URIs U =
and V, for=20
  which U is immediately relative to V, B <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be a =
collection=20
  that has U as an internal member URI. So, if the resource with URL <A=20
  href=3D"http://foo.com/bar/blah">http://foo.com/bar/blah</A> is WebDAV =
compliant=20
  and if the resource with URL <A=20
  href=3D"http://foo.com/bar/">http://foo.com/bar/</A> is WebDAV =
compliant then=20
  the resource with URL <A =
href=3D"http://foo.com/bar/">http://foo.com/bar/</A>=20
  must be a collection and must contain URL <A=20
  href=3D"http://foo.com/bar/blah">http://foo.com/bar/blah</A> as an =
internal=20
  member.=20
  <P>Collection resources <STRONG>MAY</STRONG> list the URLs of =
non-WebDAV=20
  compliant children in the HTTP URL namespace hierarchy as internal =
members but=20
  are not required to do so. For example, if the resource with URL <A=20
  href=3D"http://foo.com/bar/blah">http://foo.com/bar/blah</A> is not =
WebDAV=20
  compliant and the URL <A =
href=3D"http://foo.com/bar/">http://foo.com/bar/</A>=20
  identifies a collection then URL <BR><A=20
  href=3D"http://foo.com/bar/blah">http://foo.com/bar/blah</A> may or =
may not be=20
  an internal member of the collection with URL <A=20
  href=3D"http://foo.com/bar/">http://foo.com/bar/</A>.=20
  <P>If a WebDAV compliant resource has no WebDAV compliant children in =
the HTTP=20
  URL namespace hierarchy then the WebDAV compliant resource is not =
required to=20
  be a collection.=20
  <P>There is a standing convention that when a collection is referred =
to by its=20
  name without a trailing slash, the trailing slash is automatically =
appended.=20
  Due to this, a resource may accept a URI without a trailing "/" to =
point to a=20
  collection. In this case it <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> return a =
content-location=20
  header in the response pointing to the URI ending with the "/". For =
example,=20
  if a client invokes a method on <A=20
  href=3D"http://foo.bar/blah">http://foo.bar/blah</A> (no trailing =
slash), the=20
  resource <A href=3D"http://foo.bar/blah/">http://foo.bar/blah/</A> =
(trailing=20
  slash) may respond as if the operation were invoked on it, and should =
return a=20
  content-location header with <A=20
  href=3D"http://foo.bar/blah/">http://foo.bar/blah/</A> in it. In =
general clients=20
  <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> use the "/" form of collection names.=20
  <P>A resource <STRONG>MAY</STRONG> be a collection but not be WebDAV=20
  compliant. That is, the resource may comply with all the rules set out =
in this=20
  specification regarding how a collection is to behave without =
necessarily=20
  supporting all methods that a WebDAV compliant resource is required to =

  support. In such a case the resource may return the DAV:resourcetype =
property=20
  with the value DAV:collection but <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> return a =
DAV=20
  header containing the value "1" on an OPTIONS response.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.3>5.3</A> Creation and Retrieval of =
Collection=20
  Resources</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>This document specifies the MKCOL method to create new collection=20
  resources, rather than using the existing HTTP/1.1 PUT or POST method, =
for the=20
  following reasons:=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-13>Page 13</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>In HTTP/1.1, the PUT method is defined to store the request body at =
the=20
  location specified by the Request-URI. While a description format for =
a=20
  collection can readily be constructed for use with PUT, the =
implications of=20
  sending such a description to the server are undesirable. For example, =
if a=20
  description of a collection that omitted some existing resources were =
PUT to a=20
  server, this might be interpreted as a command to remove those =
members. This=20
  would extend PUT to perform DELETE functionality, which is undesirable =
since=20
  it changes the semantics of PUT, and makes it difficult to control =
DELETE=20
  functionality with an access control scheme based on methods.=20
  <P>While the POST method is sufficiently open-ended that a "create a=20
  collection" POST command could be constructed, this is undesirable =
because it=20
  would be difficult to separate access control for collection creation =
from=20
  other uses of POST.=20
  <P>The exact definition of the behavior of GET and PUT on collections =
is=20
  defined later in this document.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.4>5.4</A> Source Resources and Output=20
  Resources</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>For many resources, the entity returned by a GET method exactly =
matches the=20
  persistent state of the resource, for example, a GIF file stored on a =
disk.=20
  For this simple case, the URI at which a resource is accessed is =
identical to=20
  the URI at which the source (the persistent state) of the resource is=20
  accessed. This is also the case for HTML source files that are not =
processed=20
  by the server prior to transmission.=20
  <P>However, the server can sometimes process HTML resources before =
they are=20
  transmitted as a return entity body. For example, a server- =
side-include=20
  directive within an HTML file might instruct a server to replace the =
directive=20
  with another value, such as the current date. In this case, what is =
returned=20
  by GET (HTML plus date) differs from the persistent state of the =
resource=20
  (HTML plus directive). Typically there is no way to access the HTML =
resource=20
  containing the unprocessed directive.=20
  <P>Sometimes the entity returned by GET is the output of a data- =
producing=20
  process that is described by one or more source resources (that may =
not even=20
  have a location in the URI namespace). A single data-producing process =
may=20
  dynamically generate the state of a potentially large number of output =

  resources. An example of this is a CGI script that describes a =
"finger"=20
  gateway process that maps part of the namespace of a server into =
finger=20
  requests, such as <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar.org/finger_gateway/user@host">http://www.foo.b=
ar.org/finger_gateway/user@host</A>.=20

  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-14>Page 14</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>In the absence of distributed authoring capabilities, it is =
acceptable to=20
  have no mapping of source resource(s) to the URI namespace. In fact,=20
  preventing access to the source resource(s) has desirable security =
benefits.=20
  However, if remote editing of the source resource(s) is desired, the =
source=20
  resource(s) should be given a location in the URI namespace. This =
source=20
  location should not be one of the locations at which the generated =
output is=20
  retrievable, since in general it is impossible for the server to =
differentiate=20
  requests for source resources from requests for process output =
resources.=20
  There is often a many-to-many relationship between source resources =
and output=20
  resources.=20
  <P>On WebDAV compliant servers the URI of the source resource(s) may =
be stored=20
  in a link on the output resource with type DAV:source (see section =
13.10 for a=20
  description of the source link property). Storing the source URIs in =
links on=20
  the output resources places the burden of discovering the source on =
the=20
  authoring client. Note that the value of a source link is not =
guaranteed to=20
  point to the correct source. Source links may break or incorrect =
values may be=20
  entered. Also note that not all servers will allow the client to set =
the=20
  source link value. For example a server which generates source links =
on the=20
  fly for its CGI files will most likely not allow a client to set the =
source=20
  link value.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-6>6</A> Locking</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The ability to lock a resource provides a mechanism for serializing =
access=20
  to that resource. Using a lock, an authoring client can provide a =
reasonable=20
  guarantee that another principal will not modify a resource while it =
is being=20
  edited. In this way, a client can prevent the "lost update" problem.=20
  <P>This specification allows locks to vary over two client-specified=20
  parameters, the number of principals involved (exclusive vs. shared) =
and the=20
  type of access to be granted. This document defines locking for only =
one=20
  access type, write. However, the syntax is extensible, and permits the =

  eventual specification of locking for other access types.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-6.1>6.1</A> Exclusive Vs. Shared =
Locks</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The most basic form of lock is an exclusive lock. This is a lock =
where the=20
  access right in question is only granted to a single principal. The =
need for=20
  this arbitration results from a desire to avoid having to merge =
results.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-15>Page 15</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>However, there are times when the goal of a lock is not to exclude =
others=20
  from exercising an access right but rather to provide a mechanism for=20
  principals to indicate that they intend to exercise their access =
rights.=20
  Shared locks are provided for this case. A shared lock allows multiple =

  principals to receive a lock. Hence any principal with appropriate =
access can=20
  get the lock.=20
  <P>With shared locks there are two trust sets that affect a resource. =
The=20
  first trust set is created by access permissions. Principals who are =
trusted,=20
  for example, may have permission to write to the resource. Among those =
who=20
  have access permission to write to the resource, the set of principals =
who=20
  have taken out a shared lock also must trust each other, creating a=20
  (typically) smaller trust set within the access permission write set.=20
  <P>Starting with every possible principal on the Internet, in most =
situations=20
  the vast majority of these principals will not have write access to a =
given=20
  resource. Of the small number who do have write access, some =
principals may=20
  decide to guarantee their edits are free from overwrite conflicts by =
using=20
  exclusive write locks. Others may decide they trust their =
collaborators will=20
  not overwrite their work (the potential set of collaborators being the =
set of=20
  principals who have write permission) and use a shared lock, which =
informs=20
  their collaborators that a principal may be working on the resource.=20
  <P>The WebDAV extensions to HTTP do not need to provide all of the=20
  communications paths necessary for principals to coordinate their =
activities.=20
  When using shared locks, principals may use any out of band =
communication=20
  channel to coordinate their work (e.g., face-to- face interaction, =
written=20
  notes, post-it notes on the screen, telephone conversation, Email, =
etc.) The=20
  intent of a shared lock is to let collaborators know who else may be =
working=20
  on a resource.=20
  <P>Shared locks are included because experience from web distributed =
authoring=20
  systems has indicated that exclusive locks are often too rigid. An =
exclusive=20
  lock is used to enforce a particular editing process: take out an =
exclusive=20
  lock, read the resource, perform edits, write the resource, release =
the lock.=20
  This editing process has the problem that locks are not always =
properly=20
  released, for example when a program crashes, or when a lock owner =
leaves=20
  without unlocking a resource. While both timeouts and administrative =
action=20
  can be used to remove an offending lock, neither mechanism may be =
available=20
  when needed; the timeout may be long or the administrator may not be=20
  available.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-16>Page 16</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-6.2>6.2</A> Required Support</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A WebDAV compliant server is not required to support locking in any =
form.=20
  If the server does support locking it may choose to support any =
combination of=20
  exclusive and shared locks for any access types.=20
  <P>The reason for this flexibility is that locking policy strikes to =
the very=20
  heart of the resource management and versioning systems employed by =
various=20
  storage repositories. These repositories require control over what =
sort of=20
  locking will be made available. For example, some repositories only =
support=20
  shared write locks while others only provide support for exclusive =
write locks=20
  while yet others use no locking at all. As each system is sufficiently =

  different to merit exclusion of certain locking features, this =
specification=20
  leaves locking as the sole axis of negotiation within WebDAV.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-6.3>6.3</A> Lock Tokens</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A lock token is a type of state token, represented as a URI, which=20
  identifies a particular lock. A lock token is returned by every =
successful=20
  LOCK operation in the lockdiscovery property in the response body, and =
can=20
  also be found through lock discovery on a resource.=20
  <P>Lock token URIs <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be unique across all =
resources for=20
  all time. This uniqueness constraint allows lock tokens to be =
submitted across=20
  resources and servers without fear of confusion.=20
  <P>This specification provides a lock token URI scheme called =
opaquelocktoken=20
  that meets the uniqueness requirements. However resources are free to =
return=20
  any URI scheme so long as it meets the uniqueness requirements.=20
  <P>Having a lock token provides no special access rights. Anyone can =
find out=20
  anyone else's lock token by performing lock discovery. Locks=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be enforced based upon whatever authentication =
mechanism=20
  is used by the server, not based on the secrecy of the token values.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-6.4>6.4</A> opaquelocktoken Lock Token URI=20
  Scheme</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The opaquelocktoken URI scheme is designed to be unique across all=20
  resources for all time. Due to this uniqueness quality, a client may =
submit an=20
  opaque lock token in an If header on a resource other than the one =
that=20
  returned it.=20
  <P>All resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> recognize the opaquelocktoken =
scheme=20
  and, at minimum, recognize that the lock token does not refer to an=20
  outstanding lock on the resource.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-17>Page 17</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>In order to guarantee uniqueness across all resources for all time =
the=20
  opaquelocktoken requires the use of the Universal Unique Identifier =
(UUID)=20
  mechanism, as described in [ISO-11578].=20
  <P>Opaquelocktoken generators, however, have a choice of how they =
create these=20
  tokens. They can either generate a new UUID for every lock token they =
create=20
  or they can create a single UUID and then add extension characters. If =
the=20
  second method is selected then the program generating the extensions=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> guarantee that the same extension will never be =
used=20
  twice with the associated UUID.=20
  <P>OpaqueLockToken-URI =3D "opaquelocktoken:" UUID [Extension] ; The =
UUID=20
  production is the string representation of a UUID, as defined in =
[ISO-11578].=20
  Note that white space (LWS) is not allowed between elements of this=20
  production.=20
  <P>Extension =3D path ; path is defined in section 3.2.1 of <A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2068.html">RFC 2068</A> =
[<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2068.html">RFC2068</A>]=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-6.4.1>6.4.1</A> Node Field Generation =
Without the IEEE=20
  802 Address</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>UUIDs, as defined in [ISO-11578], contain a "node" field that =
contains one=20
  of the IEEE 802 addresses for the server machine. As noted in section =
17.8,=20
  there are several security risks associated with exposing a machine's =
IEEE 802=20
  address. This section provides an alternate mechanism for generating =
the=20
  "node" field of a UUID which does not employ an IEEE 802 address. =
WebDAV=20
  servers <STRONG>MAY</STRONG> use this algorithm for creating the node =
field=20
  when generating UUIDs. The text in this section is originally from an=20
  Internet-Draft by Paul Leach and Rich Salz, who are noted here to =
properly=20
  attribute their work.=20
  <P>The ideal solution is to obtain a 47 bit cryptographic quality =
random=20
  number, and use it as the low 47 bits of the node ID, with the most=20
  significant bit of the first octet of the node ID set to 1. This bit =
is the=20
  unicast/multicast bit, which will never be set in IEEE 802 addresses =
obtained=20
  from network cards; hence, there can never be a conflict between UUIDs =

  generated by machines with and without network cards.=20
  <P>If a system does not have a primitive to generate cryptographic =
quality=20
  random numbers, then in most systems there are usually a fairly large =
number=20
  of sources of randomness available from which one can be generated. =
Such=20
  sources are system specific, but often include:=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-18>Page 18</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>     - the percent of memory in use
     - the size of main memory in bytes
     - the amount of free main memory in bytes
     - the size of the paging or swap file in bytes
     - free bytes of paging or swap file
     - the total size of user virtual address space in bytes
     - the total available user address space bytes
     - the size of boot disk drive in bytes
     - the free disk space on boot drive in bytes
     - the current time
     - the amount of time since the system booted
     - the individual sizes of files in various system directories
     - the creation, last read, and modification times of files in
       various system directories
     - the utilization factors of various system resources (heap, etc.)
     - current mouse cursor position
     - current caret position
     - current number of running processes, threads
     - handles or IDs of the desktop window and the active window
     - the value of stack pointer of the caller
     - the process and thread ID of caller
     - various processor architecture specific performance counters
       (instructions executed, cache misses, TLB misses)
</PRE>
  <P>(Note that it is precisely the above kinds of sources of randomness =
that=20
  are used to seed cryptographic quality random number generators on =
systems=20
  without special hardware for their construction.)=20
  <P>In addition, items such as the computer's name and the name of the=20
  operating system, while not strictly speaking random, will help =
differentiate=20
  the results from those obtained by other systems.=20
  <P>The exact algorithm to generate a node ID using these data is =
system=20
  specific, because both the data available and the functions to obtain =
them are=20
  often very system specific. However, assuming that one can concatenate =
all the=20
  values from the randomness sources into a buffer, and that a =
cryptographic=20
  hash function such as MD5 is available, then any 6 bytes of the MD5 =
hash of=20
  the buffer, with the multicast bit (the high bit of the first byte) =
set will=20
  be an appropriately random node ID.=20
  <P>Other hash functions, such as SHA-1, can also be used. The only =
requirement=20
  is that the result be suitably random _ in the sense that the outputs =
from a=20
  set uniformly distributed inputs are themselves uniformly distributed, =
and=20
  that a single bit change in the input can be expected to cause half of =
the=20
  output bits to change.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-19>Page 19</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-6.5>6.5</A> Lock Capability =
Discovery</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Since server lock support is optional, a client trying to lock a =
resource=20
  on a server can either try the lock and hope for the best, or perform =
some=20
  form of discovery to determine what lock capabilities the server =
supports.=20
  This is known as lock capability discovery. Lock capability discovery =
differs=20
  from discovery of supported access control types, since there may be =
access=20
  control types without corresponding lock types. A client can determine =
what=20
  lock types the server supports by retrieving the supportedlock =
property.=20
  <P>Any DAV compliant resource that supports the LOCK method=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the supportedlock property.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-6.6>6.6</A> Active Lock Discovery</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>If another principal locks a resource that a principal wishes to =
access, it=20
  is useful for the second principal to be able to find out who the =
first=20
  principal is. For this purpose the lockdiscovery property is provided. =
This=20
  property lists all outstanding locks, describes their type, and where=20
  available, provides their lock token.=20
  <P>Any DAV compliant resource that supports the LOCK method=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the lockdiscovery property.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-6.7>6.7</A> Usage Considerations</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Although the locking mechanisms specified here provide some help in =

  preventing lost updates, they cannot guarantee that updates will never =
be=20
  lost. Consider the following scenario:=20
  <P>Two clients A and B are interested in editing the resource ' =
index.html'.=20
  Client A is an HTTP client rather than a WebDAV client, and so does =
not know=20
  how to perform locking. <BR>Client A doesn't lock the document, but =
does a GET=20
  and begins editing. <BR>Client B does LOCK, performs a GET and begins =
editing.=20
  <BR>Client B finishes editing, performs a PUT, then an UNLOCK. Client =
A=20
  performs a PUT, overwriting and losing all of B's changes.=20
  <P>There are several reasons why the WebDAV protocol itself cannot =
prevent=20
  this situation. First, it cannot force all clients to use locking =
because it=20
  must be compatible with HTTP clients that do not comprehend locking. =
Second,=20
  it cannot require servers to support locking because of the variety of =

  repository implementations, some of which rely on reservations and =
merging=20
  rather than on locking. Finally, being stateless, it cannot enforce a =
sequence=20
  of operations like LOCK / GET / PUT / UNLOCK.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-20>Page 20</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>WebDAV servers that support locking can reduce the likelihood that =
clients=20
  will accidentally overwrite each other's changes by requiring clients =
to lock=20
  resources before modifying them. Such servers would effectively =
prevent HTTP=20
  1.0 and HTTP 1.1 clients from modifying resources.=20
  <P>WebDAV clients can be good citizens by using a lock / retrieve / =
write=20
  /unlock sequence of operations (at least by default) whenever they =
interact=20
  with a WebDAV server that supports locking.=20
  <P>HTTP 1.1 clients can be good citizens, avoiding overwriting other =
clients'=20
  changes, by using entity tags in If-Match headers with any requests =
that would=20
  modify resources.=20
  <P>Information managers may attempt to prevent overwrites by =
implementing=20
  client-side procedures requiring locking before modifying WebDAV =
resources.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-7>7</A> Write Lock</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>This section describes the semantics specific to the write lock =
type. The=20
  write lock is a specific instance of a lock type, and is the only lock =
type=20
  described in this specification.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-7.1>7.1</A> Methods Restricted by Write =
Locks</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A write lock <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> prevent a principal without the =
lock=20
  from successfully executing a PUT, POST, PROPPATCH, LOCK, UNLOCK, =
MOVE,=20
  DELETE, or MKCOL on the locked resource. All other current methods, =
GET in=20
  particular, function independently of the lock.=20
  <P>Note, however, that as new methods are created it will be necessary =
to=20
  specify how they interact with a write lock.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-7.2>7.2</A> Write Locks and Lock =
Tokens</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A successful request for an exclusive or shared write lock=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> result in the generation of a unique lock token=20
  associated with the requesting principal. Thus if five principals have =
a=20
  shared write lock on the same resource there will be five lock tokens, =
one for=20
  each principal.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-7.3>7.3</A> Write Locks and =
Properties</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>While those without a write lock may not alter a property on a =
resource it=20
  is still possible for the values of live properties to change, even =
while=20
  locked, due to the requirements of their schemas.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-21>Page 21</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>Only dead properties and live properties defined to respect locks =
are=20
  guaranteed not to change while write locked.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-7.4>7.4</A> Write Locks and Null =
Resources</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>It is possible to assert a write lock on a null resource in order =
to lock=20
  the name.=20
  <P>A write locked null resource, referred to as a lock-null resource,=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> respond with a 404 (Not Found) or 405 (Method =
Not=20
  Allowed) to any HTTP/1.1 or DAV methods except for PUT, MKCOL, =
OPTIONS,=20
  PROPFIND, LOCK, and UNLOCK. A lock-null resource <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> =
appear=20
  as a member of its parent collection. Additionally the lock-null =
resource=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> have defined on it all mandatory DAV properties. =
Most of=20
  these properties, such as all the get* properties, will have no value =
as a=20
  lock-null resource does not support the GET method. Lock-Null =
resources=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> have defined values for lockdiscovery and=20
  <BR>supportedlock properties.=20
  <P>Until a method such as PUT or MKCOL is successfully executed on the =

  lock-null resource the resource <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> stay in the =
lock-null=20
  state. However, once a PUT or MKCOL is successfully executed on a =
lock-null=20
  resource the resource ceases to be in the lock-null state.=20
  <P>If the resource is unlocked, for any reason, without a PUT, MKCOL, =
or=20
  similar method having been successfully executed upon it then the =
resource=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> return to the null state.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-7.5>7.5</A> Write Locks and =
Collections</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A write lock on a collection, whether created by a "Depth: 0" or =
"Depth:=20
  infinity" lock request, prevents the addition or removal of member =
URIs of the=20
  collection by non-lock owners. As a consequence, when a principal =
issues a PUT=20
  or POST request to create a new resource under a URI which needs to be =
an=20
  internal member of a write locked collection to maintain HTTP =
namespace=20
  consistency, or issues a DELETE to remove a resource which has a URI =
which is=20
  an existing internal member URI of a write locked collection, this =
request=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> fail if the principal does not have a write lock =
on the=20
  collection.=20
  <P>However, if a write lock request is issued to a collection =
containing=20
  member URIs identifying resources that are currently locked in a =
manner which=20
  conflicts with the write lock, the request <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> fail =
with a=20
  423 (Locked) status code.=20
  <P>If a lock owner causes the URI of a resource to be added as an =
internal=20
  member URI of a locked collection then the new resource =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG>=20
  be automatically added to the lock. This is the only mechanism that=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-22>Page 22</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>allows a resource to be added to a write lock. Thus, for example, =
if the=20
  collection /a/b/ is write locked and the resource /c is moved to <PRE> =
  /a/b/c then resource /a/b/c will be added to the write lock.
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-7.6>7.6</A> Write Locks and the If Request=20
  Header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>If a user agent is not required to have knowledge about a lock when =

  requesting an operation on a locked resource, the following scenario =
might=20
  occur. Program A, run by User A, takes out a write lock on a resource. =
Program=20
  B, also run by User A, has no knowledge of the lock taken out by =
Program A,=20
  yet performs a PUT to the locked resource. In this scenario, the PUT =
succeeds=20
  because locks are associated with a principal, not a program, and thus =
program=20
  B, because it is acting with principal A's credential, is allowed to =
perform=20
  the PUT. However, had program B known about the lock, it would not =
have=20
  overwritten the resource, preferring instead to present a dialog box=20
  describing the conflict to the user. Due to this scenario, a mechanism =
is=20
  needed to prevent different programs from accidentally ignoring locks =
taken=20
  out by other programs with the same authorization.=20
  <P>In order to prevent these collisions a lock token =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be=20
  submitted by an authorized principal in the If header for all locked =
resources=20
  that a method may interact with or the method <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> =
fail. For=20
  example, if a resource is to be moved and both the source and =
destination are=20
  locked then two lock tokens must be submitted, one for the source and =
the=20
  other for the destination.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-7.6.1>7.6.1</A> Example - Write =
Lock</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Request=20
  <P>COPY /~fielding/index.html HTTP/1.1 <BR>Host: www.ics.uci.edu=20
  <BR>Destination: <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.ics.uci.edu/users/f/fielding/index.html">http://www.ic=
s.uci.edu/users/f/fielding/index.html</A>=20
  If: &lt;<A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.ics.uci.edu/users/f/fielding/index.html">http://www.ic=
s.uci.edu/users/f/fielding/index.html</A>&gt;=20
  <BR>(&lt;opaquelocktoken:f81d4fae-7dec-11d0-a765-00a0c91e6bf6&gt;)=20
  <P>&gt;&gt;Response=20
  <P>HTTP/1.1 204 No Content=20
  <P>In this example, even though both the source and destination are =
locked,=20
  only one lock token must be submitted, for the lock on the =
destination. This=20
  is because the source resource is not modified by a COPY, and hence =
unaffected=20
  by the write lock. In this example, user agent authentication has =
previously=20
  occurred via a mechanism outside the scope of the HTTP protocol, in =
the=20
  underlying transport layer.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-23>Page 23</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-7.7>7.7</A> Write Locks and =
COPY/MOVE</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A COPY method invocation <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> duplicate any =
write=20
  locks active on the source. However, as previously noted, if the COPY =
copies=20
  the resource into a collection that is locked with "Depth: infinity", =
then the=20
  resource will be added to the lock.=20
  <P>A successful MOVE request on a write locked resource <STRONG>MUST=20
  NOT</STRONG> move the write lock with the resource. However, the =
resource is=20
  subject to being added to an existing lock at the destination, as =
specified in=20
  section 7.5. For example, if the MOVE makes the resource a child of a=20
  collection that is locked with "Depth: infinity", then the resource =
will be=20
  added to that collection's lock. Additionally, if a resource locked =
with=20
  "Depth: infinity" is moved to a destination that is within the scope =
of the=20
  same lock (e.g., within the namespace tree covered by the lock), the =
moved=20
  resource will again be a added to the lock. In both these examples, as =

  specified in section 7.6, an If header must be submitted containing a =
lock=20
  token for both the source and destination.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-7.8>7.8</A> Refreshing Write Locks</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A client <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> submit the same write lock =
request=20
  twice. Note that a client is always aware it is resubmitting the same =
lock=20
  request because it must include the lock token in the If header in =
order to=20
  make the request for a resource that is already locked.=20
  <P>However, a client may submit a LOCK method with an If header but =
without a=20
  body. This form of LOCK <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> only be used to =
"refresh" a=20
  lock. Meaning, at minimum, that any timers associated with the lock=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be re-set.=20
  <P>A server may return a Timeout header with a lock refresh that is =
different=20
  than the Timeout header returned when the lock was originally =
requested.=20
  Additionally clients may submit Timeout headers of arbitrary value =
with their=20
  lock refresh requests. Servers, as always, may ignore Timeout headers=20
  submitted by the client.=20
  <P>If an error is received in response to a refresh LOCK request the =
client=20
  <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> assume that the lock was not refreshed.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8>8</A> HTTP Methods for Distributed=20
Authoring</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The following new HTTP methods use XML as a request and response =
format.=20
  All DAV compliant clients and resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> use XML =
parsers=20
  that are compliant with [REC-XML]. All XML used in either requests or=20
  responses <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be, at minimum, well formed. If a =
server=20
  receives=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-24>Page 24</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>ill-formed XML in a request it <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> reject the =
entire=20
  request with a 400 (Bad Request). If a client receives ill-formed XML =
in a=20
  response then it <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> assume anything about the =
outcome=20
  of the executed method and <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> treat the server as =

  malfunctioning.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.1>8.1</A> PROPFIND</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The PROPFIND method retrieves properties defined on the resource =
identified=20
  by the Request-URI, if the resource does not have any internal =
members, or on=20
  the resource identified by the Request-URI and potentially its member=20
  resources, if the resource is a collection that has internal member =
URIs. All=20
  DAV compliant resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the PROPFIND =
method and=20
  the propfind XML element (section 12.14) along with all XML elements =
defined=20
  for use with that element.=20
  <P>A client may submit a Depth header with a value of "0", "1", or =
"infinity"=20
  with a PROPFIND on a collection resource with internal member URIs. =
DAV=20
  compliant servers <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the "0", "1" and =
"infinity"=20
  behaviors. By default, the PROPFIND method without a Depth header=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> act as if a "Depth: infinity" header was =
included.=20
  <P>A client may submit a propfind XML element in the body of the =
request=20
  method describing what information is being requested. It is possible =
to=20
  request particular property values, all property values, or a list of =
the=20
  names of the resource's properties. A client may choose not to submit =
a=20
  request body. An empty PROPFIND request body <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be =
treated=20
  as a request for the names and values of all properties.=20
  <P>All servers <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support returning a response of =
content=20
  type text/xml or application/xml that contains a multistatus XML =
element that=20
  describes the results of the attempts to retrieve the various =
properties.=20
  <P>If there is an error retrieving a property then a proper error =
result=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be included in the response. A request to =
retrieve the=20
  value of a property which does not exist is an error and =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG>=20
  be noted, if the response uses a multistatus XML element, with a =
response XML=20
  element which contains a 404 (Not Found) status value.=20
  <P>Consequently, the multistatus XML element for a collection resource =
with=20
  member URIs <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> include a response XML element for =
each=20
  member URI of the collection, to whatever depth was requested. Each =
response=20
  XML element <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> contain an href XML element that =
gives the=20
  URI of the resource on which the properties in the prop XML element =
are=20
  defined. Results for a PROPFIND on a collection resource with internal =
member=20
  URIs are returned as a flat list whose order of entries is not =
significant.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-25>Page 25</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>In the case of allprop and propname, if a principal does not have =
the right=20
  to know whether a particular property exists then the property should =
be=20
  silently excluded from the response.=20
  <P>The results of this method <STRONG>SHOULD NOT</STRONG> be cached.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.1.1>8.1.1</A> Example - Retrieving Named=20
  Properties</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Request=20
  <P>PROPFIND /file HTTP/1.1 <BR>Host: www.foo.bar <BR>Content-type: =
text/xml;=20
  charset=3D"utf-8" <BR>Content-Length: xxxx=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:propfind xmlns:D=3D"DAV:"&gt;
     &lt;D:prop xmlns:R=3D"<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/boxschema/">http://www.foo.bar/boxschema/</A>"=
&gt;
          &lt;R:bigbox/&gt;
          &lt;R:author/&gt;
          &lt;R:DingALing/&gt;
          &lt;R:Random/&gt;
     &lt;/D:prop&gt;
   &lt;/D:propfind&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Response=20
  <P>HTTP/1.1 207 Multi-Status <BR>Content-Type: text/xml; =
charset=3D"utf-8"=20
  <BR>Content-Length: xxxx=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:multistatus xmlns:D=3D"DAV:"&gt;
     &lt;D:response&gt;
          &lt;D:href&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/file</D:href">http://www.foo.bar/file</D:HREF<=
 a>&gt;
          &lt;D:propstat&gt;
               &lt;D:prop xmlns:R=3D"<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/boxschema/">http://www.foo.bar/boxschema/</A>"=
&gt;
                    &lt;R:bigbox&gt;
                         &lt;R:BoxType&gt;Box type A&lt;/R:BoxType&gt;
                    &lt;/R:bigbox&gt;
                    &lt;R:author&gt;
                         &lt;R:Name&gt;J.J. Johnson&lt;/R:Name&gt;
                    &lt;/R:author&gt;
               &lt;/D:prop&gt;
               &lt;D:status&gt;HTTP/1.1 200 OK&lt;/D:status&gt;
          &lt;/D:propstat&gt;
          &lt;D:propstat&gt;
               =
&lt;D:prop&gt;&lt;R:DingALing/&gt;&lt;R:Random/&gt;&lt;/D:prop&gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-26>Page 26</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>               &lt;D:status&gt;HTTP/1.1 403 =
Forbidden&lt;/D:status&gt;
               &lt;D:responsedescription&gt; The user does not have =
access to
   the DingALing property.
               &lt;/D:responsedescription&gt;
          &lt;/D:propstat&gt;
     &lt;/D:response&gt;
     &lt;D:responsedescription&gt; There has been an access violation =
error.
     &lt;/D:responsedescription&gt;
   &lt;/D:multistatus&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>In this example, PROPFIND is executed on a non-collection resource =
<A=20
  href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/file">http://www.foo.bar/file</A>. The =
propfind XML=20
  element specifies the name of four properties whose values are being=20
  requested. In this case only two properties were returned, since the =
principal=20
  issuing the request did not have sufficient access rights to see the =
third and=20
  fourth properties.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.1.2>8.1.2</A> Example - Using allprop to =
Retrieve=20
  All Properties</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Request=20
  <P>PROPFIND /container/ HTTP/1.1 <BR>Host: www.foo.bar <BR>Depth: 1=20
  <BR>Content-Type: text/xml; charset=3D"utf-8" <BR>Content-Length: xxxx =

  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:propfind xmlns:D=3D"DAV:"&gt;
     &lt;D:allprop/&gt;
   &lt;/D:propfind&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Response=20
  <P>HTTP/1.1 207 Multi-Status <BR>Content-Type: text/xml; =
charset=3D"utf-8"=20
  <BR>Content-Length: xxxx=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:multistatus xmlns:D=3D"DAV:"&gt;
     &lt;D:response&gt;
          &lt;D:href&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/container/</D:href">http://www.foo.bar/contain=
er/</D:HREF< a>&gt;
          &lt;D:propstat&gt;
               &lt;D:prop xmlns:R=3D"<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/boxschema/">http://www.foo.bar/boxschema/</A>"=
&gt;
                    &lt;R:bigbox&gt;
                         &lt;R:BoxType&gt;Box type A&lt;/R:BoxType&gt;
                    &lt;/R:bigbox&gt;
                    &lt;R:author&gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
