  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.2>8.2</A> PROPPATCH</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The PROPPATCH method processes instructions specified in the =
request body=20
  to set and/or remove properties defined on the resource identified by =
the=20
  Request-URI.=20
  <P>All DAV compliant resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the =
PROPPATCH=20
  method and <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> process instructions that are =
specified using=20
  the <BR>propertyupdate, set, and remove XML elements of the DAV =
schema.=20
  Execution of the directives in this method is, of course, subject to =
access=20
  control constraints. DAV compliant resources <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> =
support=20
  the setting of arbitrary dead properties.=20
  <P>The request message body of a PROPPATCH method =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG>=20
  contain the propertyupdate XML element. Instruction processing=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> occur in the order instructions are received =
(i.e., from=20
  top to bottom). Instructions <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> either all be =
executed or=20
  none executed. Thus if any error occurs during processing all executed =

  instructions <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be undone and a proper error result =

  returned. Instruction processing details can be found in the =
definition of the=20
  set and remove instructions in section 12.13.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.2.1>8.2.1</A> Status Codes for use with =
207=20
  (Multi-Status)</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The following are examples of response codes one would expect to be =
used in=20
  a 207 (Multi-Status) response for this method. Note, however, that =
unless=20
  explicitly prohibited any 2/3/4/5xx series response code may be used =
in a 207=20
  (Multi-Status) response.=20
  <P>200 (OK) - The command succeeded. As there can be a mixture of sets =
and=20
  removes in a body, a 201 (Created) seems inappropriate.=20
  <P>403 (Forbidden) - The client, for reasons the server chooses not to =

  specify, cannot alter one of the properties.=20
  <P>409 (Conflict) - The client has provided a value whose semantics =
are not=20
  appropriate for the property. This includes trying to set read- only=20
  properties.=20
  <P>423 (Locked) - The specified resource is locked and the client =
either is=20
  not a lock owner or the lock type requires a lock token to be =
submitted and=20
  the client did not submit it.=20
  <P>507 (Insufficient Storage) - The server did not have sufficient =
space to=20
  record the property.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-32>Page 32</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.2.2>8.2.2</A> Example - PROPPATCH</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Request=20
  <P>PROPPATCH /bar.html HTTP/1.1 <BR>Host: www.foo.com =
<BR>Content-Type:=20
  text/xml; charset=3D"utf-8" <BR>Content-Length: xxxx=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:propertyupdate xmlns:D=3D"DAV:"
   xmlns:Z=3D"<A =
href=3D"http://www.w3.com/standards/z39.50/">http://www.w3.com/standards/=
z39.50/</A>"&gt;
     &lt;D:set&gt;
          &lt;D:prop&gt;
               &lt;Z:authors&gt;
                    &lt;Z:Author&gt;Jim Whitehead&lt;/Z:Author&gt;
                    &lt;Z:Author&gt;Roy Fielding&lt;/Z:Author&gt;
               &lt;/Z:authors&gt;
          &lt;/D:prop&gt;
     &lt;/D:set&gt;
     &lt;D:remove&gt;
          &lt;D:prop&gt;&lt;Z:Copyright-Owner/&gt;&lt;/D:prop&gt;
     &lt;/D:remove&gt;
   &lt;/D:propertyupdate&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Response=20
  <P>HTTP/1.1 207 Multi-Status <BR>Content-Type: text/xml; =
charset=3D"utf-8"=20
  <BR>Content-Length: xxxx=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:multistatus xmlns:D=3D"DAV:"
   xmlns:Z=3D"<A =
href=3D"http://www.w3.com/standards/z39.50">http://www.w3.com/standards/z=
39.50</A>"&gt;
     &lt;D:response&gt;
          &lt;D:href&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.com/bar.html</D:href">http://www.foo.com/bar.html<=
/D:HREF< a>&gt;
          &lt;D:propstat&gt;
               &lt;D:prop&gt;&lt;Z:Authors/&gt;&lt;/D:prop&gt;
               &lt;D:status&gt;HTTP/1.1 424 Failed =
Dependency&lt;/D:status&gt;
          &lt;/D:propstat&gt;
          &lt;D:propstat&gt;
               &lt;D:prop&gt;&lt;Z:Copyright-Owner/&gt;&lt;/D:prop&gt;
               &lt;D:status&gt;HTTP/1.1 409 Conflict&lt;/D:status&gt;
          &lt;/D:propstat&gt;
          &lt;D:responsedescription&gt; Copyright Owner can not be =
deleted or
   altered.&lt;/D:responsedescription&gt;
     &lt;/D:response&gt;
   &lt;/D:multistatus&gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-33>Page 33</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>In this example, the client requests the server to set the value of =
the <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.w3.com/standards/z39.50/Authors">http://www.w3.com/sta=
ndards/z39.50/Authors</A>=20
  property, and to remove the property <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.w3.com/standards/z39.50/Copyright-">http://www.w3.com/=
standards/z39.50/Copyright-</A>=20
  Owner. Since the Copyright-Owner property could not be removed, no =
property=20
  modifications occur. The 424 (Failed Dependency) status code for the =
Authors=20
  property indicates this action would have succeeded if it were not for =
the=20
  conflict with removing the Copyright-Owner property.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.3>8.3</A> MKCOL Method</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The MKCOL method is used to create a new collection. All DAV =
compliant=20
  resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the MKCOL method.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.3.1>8.3.1</A> Request</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>MKCOL creates a new collection resource at the location specified =
by the=20
  Request-URI. If the resource identified by the Request-URI is non-null =
then=20
  the MKCOL <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> fail. During MKCOL processing, a =
server=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> make the Request-URI a member of its parent =
collection,=20
  unless the Request-URI is "/". If no such ancestor exists, the method=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> fail. When the MKCOL operation creates a new =
collection=20
  resource, all ancestors <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> already exist, or the =
method=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> fail with a 409 (Conflict) status code. For =
example, if=20
  a request to create collection /a/b/c/d/ is made, and neither /a/b/ =
nor=20
  /a/b/c/ exists, the request must fail.=20
  <P>When MKCOL is invoked without a request body, the newly created =
collection=20
  <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> have no members.=20
  <P>A MKCOL request message may contain a message body. The behavior of =
a MKCOL=20
  request when the body is present is limited to creating collections, =
members=20
  of a collection, bodies of members and properties on the collections =
or=20
  members. If the server receives a MKCOL request entity type it does =
not=20
  support or understand it <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> respond with a 415 =
(Unsupported=20
  Media Type) status code. The exact behavior of MKCOL for various =
request media=20
  types is undefined in this document, and will be specified in separate =

  documents.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.3.2>8.3.2</A> Status Codes</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Responses from a MKCOL request <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> be cached =
as MKCOL=20
  has non- idempotent semantics.=20
  <P>201 (Created) - The collection or structured resource was created =
in its=20
  entirety.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-34>Page 34</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>403 (Forbidden) - This indicates at least one of two conditions: 1) =
the=20
  server does not allow the creation of collections at the given =
location in its=20
  namespace, or 2) the parent collection of the Request-URI exists but =
cannot=20
  accept members.=20
  <P>405 (Method Not Allowed) - MKCOL can only be executed on a=20
  deleted/non-existent resource.=20
  <P>409 (Conflict) - A collection cannot be made at the Request-URI =
until one=20
  or more intermediate collections have been created.=20
  <P>415 (Unsupported Media Type)- The server does not support the =
request type=20
  of the body.=20
  <P>507 (Insufficient Storage) - The resource does not have sufficient =
space to=20
  record the state of the resource after the execution of this method.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.3.3>8.3.3</A> Example - MKCOL</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>This example creates a collection called /webdisc/xfiles/ on the =
server=20
  www.server.org.=20
  <P>&gt;&gt;Request=20
  <P>MKCOL /webdisc/xfiles/ HTTP/1.1 <BR>Host: www.server.org=20
  <P>&gt;&gt;Response=20
  <P>HTTP/1.1 201 Created=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.4>8.4</A> GET, HEAD for =
Collections</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The semantics of GET are unchanged when applied to a collection, =
since GET=20
  is defined as, "retrieve whatever information (in the form of an =
entity) is=20
  identified by the Request-URI" [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2068.html">RFC2068</A>]. =
GET when=20
  applied to a collection may return the contents of an "index.html" =
resource, a=20
  human-readable view of the contents of the collection, or something =
else=20
  altogether. Hence it is possible that the result of a GET on a =
collection will=20
  bear no correlation to the membership of the collection.=20
  <P>Similarly, since the definition of HEAD is a GET without a response =
message=20
  body, the semantics of HEAD are unmodified when applied to collection=20
  resources.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-35>Page 35</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.5>8.5</A> POST for Collections</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Since by definition the actual function performed by POST is =
determined by=20
  the server and often depends on the particular resource, the behavior =
of POST=20
  when applied to collections cannot be meaningfully modified because it =
is=20
  largely undefined. Thus the semantics of POST are unmodified when =
applied to a=20
  collection.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.6>8.6</A> DELETE</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.6.1>8.6.1</A> DELETE for Non-Collection=20
  Resources</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>If the DELETE method is issued to a non-collection resource whose =
URIs are=20
  an internal member of one or more collections, then during DELETE =
processing a=20
  server <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> remove any URI for the resource =
identified by the=20
  Request-URI from collections which contain it as a member.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.6.2>8.6.2</A> DELETE for =
Collections</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The DELETE method on a collection <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> act as if a =
"Depth:=20
  infinity" header was used on it. A client <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> =
submit a=20
  Depth header with a DELETE on a collection with any value but =
infinity.=20
  <P>DELETE instructs that the collection specified in the Request-URI =
and all=20
  resources identified by its internal member URIs are to be deleted.=20
  <P>If any resource identified by a member URI cannot be deleted then =
all of=20
  the member's ancestors <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> be deleted, so as to =
maintain=20
  namespace consistency.=20
  <P>Any headers included with DELETE <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be applied =
in=20
  processing every resource to be deleted.=20
  <P>When the DELETE method has completed processing it =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG>=20
  result in a consistent namespace.=20
  <P>If an error occurs with a resource other than the resource =
identified in=20
  the Request-URI then the response <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be a 207=20
  (Multi-Status). 424 (Failed Dependency) errors <STRONG>SHOULD =
NOT</STRONG> be=20
  in the 207 (Multi- Status). They can be safely left out because the =
client=20
  will know that the ancestors of a resource could not be deleted when =
the=20
  client receives an error for the ancestor's progeny. Additionally 204 =
(No=20
  Content) errors <STRONG>SHOULD NOT</STRONG> be returned in the 207=20
  (Multi-Status). The reason for this prohibition is that 204 (No =
Content) is=20
  the default success code.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-36>Page 36</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.6.2.1>8.6.2.1</A> Example - =
DELETE</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Request=20
  <P>DELETE /container/ HTTP/1.1 <BR>Host: www.foo.bar=20
  <P>&gt;&gt;Response=20
  <P>HTTP/1.1 207 Multi-Status <BR>Content-Type: text/xml; =
charset=3D"utf-8"=20
  <BR>Content-Length: xxxx=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;d:multistatus xmlns:d=3D"DAV:"&gt;
     &lt;d:response&gt;
          &lt;d:href&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/container/resource3</d:href">http://www.foo.ba=
r/container/resource3</D:HREF< a>&gt;
          &lt;d:status&gt;HTTP/1.1 423 Locked&lt;/d:status&gt;
     &lt;/d:response&gt;
   &lt;/d:multistatus&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>In this example the attempt to delete <BR><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/container/resource3">http://www.foo.bar/contai=
ner/resource3</A>=20
  failed because it is locked, and no lock token was submitted with the =
request.=20
  Consequently, the attempt to delete <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/container/">http://www.foo.bar/container/</A> =
also=20
  failed. Thus the client knows that the attempt to delete <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/container/">http://www.foo.bar/container/</A> =
must=20
  have also failed since the parent can not be deleted unless its child =
has also=20
  been deleted. Even though a Depth header has not been included, a =
depth of=20
  infinity is assumed because the method is on a collection.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.7>8.7</A> PUT</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.7.1>8.7.1</A> PUT for Non-Collection=20
  Resources</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A PUT performed on an existing resource replaces the GET response =
entity of=20
  the resource. Properties defined on the resource may be recomputed =
during PUT=20
  processing but are not otherwise affected. For example, if a server =
recognizes=20
  the content type of the request body, it may be able to automatically =
extract=20
  information that could be profitably exposed as properties.=20
  <P>A PUT that would result in the creation of a resource without an=20
  appropriately scoped parent collection <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> fail with =
a 409=20
  (Conflict).=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-37>Page 37</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.7.2>8.7.2</A> PUT for Collections</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>As defined in the HTTP/1.1 specification [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2068.html">RFC2068</A>], =
the "PUT=20
  method requests that the enclosed entity be stored under the supplied=20
  Request-URI." Since submission of an entity representing a collection =
would=20
  implicitly encode creation and deletion of resources, this =
specification=20
  intentionally does not define a transmission format for creating a =
collection=20
  using PUT. Instead, the MKCOL method is defined to create collections. =

  <P>When the PUT operation creates a new non-collection resource all =
ancestors=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> already exist. If all ancestors do not exist, =
the method=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> fail with a 409 (Conflict) status code. For =
example, if=20
  resource /a/b/c/d.html is to be created and /a/b/c/ does not exist, =
then the=20
  request must fail.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.8>8.8</A> COPY Method</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The COPY method creates a duplicate of the source resource, =
identified by=20
  the Request-URI, in the destination resource, identified by the URI in =
the=20
  Destination header. The Destination header <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be =
present.=20
  The exact behavior of the COPY method depends on the type of the =
source=20
  resource.=20
  <P>All WebDAV compliant resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the =
COPY=20
  method. However, support for the COPY method does not guarantee the =
ability to=20
  copy a resource. For example, separate programs may control resources =
on the=20
  same server. As a result, it may not be possible to copy a resource to =
a=20
  location that appears to be on the same server.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.8.1>8.8.1</A> COPY for HTTP/1.1 =
resources</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>When the source resource is not a collection the result of the COPY =
method=20
  is the creation of a new resource at the destination whose state and =
behavior=20
  match that of the source resource as closely as possible. After a =
successful=20
  COPY invocation, all properties on the source resource =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG>=20
  be duplicated on the destination resource, subject to modifying =
headers and=20
  XML elements, following the definition for copying properties. Since =
the=20
  environment at the destination may be different than at the source due =
to=20
  factors outside the scope of control of the server, such as the =
absence of=20
  resources required for correct operation, it may not be possible to =
completely=20
  duplicate the behavior of the resource at the destination. Subsequent=20
  alterations to the destination resource will not modify the source =
resource.=20
  Subsequent alterations to the source resource will not modify the =
destination=20
  resource.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-38>Page 38</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.8.2>8.8.2</A> COPY for Properties</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The following section defines how properties on a resource are =
handled=20
  during a COPY operation.=20
  <P>Live properties <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> be duplicated as =
identically=20
  behaving live properties at the destination resource. If a property =
cannot be=20
  copied live, then its value <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be duplicated,=20
  octet-for-octet, in an identically named, dead property on the =
destination=20
  resource subject to the effects of the propertybehavior XML element.=20
  <P>The propertybehavior XML element can specify that properties are =
copied on=20
  best effort, that all live properties must be successfully copied or =
the=20
  method must fail, or that a specified list of live properties must be=20
  successfully copied or the method must fail. The propertybehavior XML =
element=20
  is defined in section 12.12.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.8.3>8.8.3</A> COPY for =
Collections</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The COPY method on a collection without a Depth header=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> act as if a Depth header with value "infinity" =
was=20
  included. A client may submit a Depth header on a COPY on a collection =
with a=20
  value of "0" or "infinity". DAV compliant servers =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG>=20
  support the "0" and "infinity" Depth header behaviors.=20
  <P>A COPY of depth infinity instructs that the collection resource =
identified=20
  by the Request-URI is to be copied to the location identified by the =
URI in=20
  the Destination header, and all its internal member resources are to =
be copied=20
  to a location relative to it, recursively through all levels of the =
collection=20
  hierarchy.=20
  <P>A COPY of "Depth: 0" only instructs that the collection and its =
properties=20
  but not resources identified by its internal member URIs, are to be =
copied.=20
  <P>Any headers included with a COPY <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be applied =
in=20
  processing every resource to be copied with the exception of the =
Destination=20
  header.=20
  <P>The Destination header only specifies the destination URI for the=20
  Request-URI. When applied to members of the collection identified by =
the=20
  Request-URI the value of Destination is to be modified to reflect the =
current=20
  location in the hierarchy. So, if the Request- URI is <PRE>   /a/ with =
Host header value <A href=3D"http://fun.com/">http://fun.com/</A> and =
the Destination is
   <A href=3D"http://fun.com/b/">http://fun.com/b/</A> then when <A =
href=3D"http://fun.com/a/c/d">http://fun.com/a/c/d</A> is processed it =
must
   use a Destination of <A =
href=3D"http://fun.com/b/c/d">http://fun.com/b/c/d</A>.
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-39>Page 39</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>When the COPY method has completed processing it =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG> have=20
  created a consistent namespace at the destination (see section 5.1 for =
the=20
  definition of namespace consistency). However, if an error occurs =
while=20
  copying an internal collection, the server <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> =
copy any=20
  resources identified by members of this collection (i.e., the server =
must skip=20
  this subtree), as this would create an inconsistent namespace. After =
detecting=20
  an error, the COPY operation <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> try to finish as =
much of=20
  the original copy operation as possible (i.e., the server should still =
attempt=20
  to copy other subtrees and their members, that are not descendents of =
an=20
  error-causing collection). So, for example, if an infinite depth copy=20
  operation is performed on collection /a/, which contains collections =
/a/b/ and=20
  /a/c/, and an error occurs copying /a/b/, an attempt should still be =
made to=20
  copy <PRE>   /a/c/. Similarly, after encountering an error copying a =
non-
   collection resource as part of an infinite depth copy, the server
   <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> try to finish as much of the original copy =
operation as
   possible.
</PRE>
  <P>If an error in executing the COPY method occurs with a resource =
other than=20
  the resource identified in the Request-URI then the response=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be a 207 (Multi-Status).=20
  <P>The 424 (Failed Dependency) status code <STRONG>SHOULD NOT</STRONG> =
be=20
  returned in the 207 (Multi-Status) response from a COPY method. These=20
  responses can be safely omitted because the client will know that the =
progeny=20
  of a resource could not be copied when the client receives an error =
for the=20
  parent. Additionally 201 (Created)/204 (No Content) status codes=20
  <STRONG>SHOULD NOT</STRONG> be returned as values in 207 =
(Multi-Status)=20
  responses from COPY methods. They, too, can be safely omitted because =
they are=20
  the default success codes.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.8.4>8.8.4</A> COPY and the Overwrite =
Header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>If a resource exists at the destination and the Overwrite header is =
"T"=20
  then prior to performing the copy the server <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> =
perform a=20
  DELETE with "Depth: infinity" on the destination resource. If the =
Overwrite=20
  header is set to "F" then the operation will fail.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.8.5>8.8.5</A> Status Codes</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>201 (Created) - The source resource was successfully copied. The =
copy=20
  operation resulted in the creation of a new resource.=20
  <P>204 (No Content) - The source resource was successfully copied to a =

  pre-existing destination resource.=20
  <P>403 (Forbidden) _ The source and destination URIs are the same.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-40>Page 40</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>409 (Conflict) _ A resource cannot be created at the destination =
until one=20
  or more intermediate collections have been created.=20
  <P>412 (Precondition Failed) - The server was unable to maintain the =
liveness=20
  of the properties listed in the propertybehavior XML element or the =
Overwrite=20
  header is "F" and the state of the destination resource is non-null.=20
  <P>423 (Locked) - The destination resource was locked.=20
  <P>502 (Bad Gateway) - This may occur when the destination is on =
another=20
  server and the destination server refuses to accept the resource.=20
  <P>507 (Insufficient Storage) - The destination resource does not have =

  sufficient space to record the state of the resource after the =
execution of=20
  this method.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.8.6>8.8.6</A> Example - COPY with =
Overwrite</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>This example shows resource <BR><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.ics.uci.edu/~fielding/index.html">http://www.ics.uci.e=
du/~fielding/index.html</A>=20
  being copied to the location <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.ics.uci.edu/users/f/fielding/index.html">http://www.ic=
s.uci.edu/users/f/fielding/index.html</A>.=20
  The 204 (No Content) status code indicates the existing resource at =
the=20
  destination was overwritten.=20
  <P>&gt;&gt;Request=20
  <P>COPY /~fielding/index.html HTTP/1.1 <BR>Host: www.ics.uci.edu=20
  <BR>Destination: <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.ics.uci.edu/users/f/fielding/index.html">http://www.ic=
s.uci.edu/users/f/fielding/index.html</A>=20

  <P>&gt;&gt;Response=20
  <P>HTTP/1.1 204 No Content=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.8.7>8.8.7</A> Example - COPY with No=20
  Overwrite</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The following example shows the same copy operation being =
performed, but=20
  with the Overwrite header set to "F." A response of 412 (Precondition =
Failed)=20
  is returned because the destination resource has a non-null state.=20
  <P>&gt;&gt;Request=20
  <P>COPY /~fielding/index.html HTTP/1.1 <BR>Host: www.ics.uci.edu=20
  <BR>Destination: <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.ics.uci.edu/users/f/fielding/index.html">http://www.ic=
s.uci.edu/users/f/fielding/index.html</A>=20
  Overwrite: F=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-41>Page 41</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Response=20
  <P>HTTP/1.1 412 Precondition Failed=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.8.8>8.8.8</A> Example - COPY of a=20
Collection</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Request=20
  <P>COPY /container/ HTTP/1.1 <BR>Host: www.foo.bar <BR>Destination: <A =

  =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/othercontainer/">http://www.foo.bar/otherconta=
iner/</A>=20
  <BR>Depth: infinity <BR>Content-Type: text/xml; charset=3D"utf-8"=20
  <BR>Content-Length: xxxx=20
  <P><PRE>      &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
      &lt;d:propertybehavior xmlns:d=3D"DAV:"&gt;
        &lt;d:keepalive&gt;*&lt;/d:keepalive&gt;
      &lt;/d:propertybehavior&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Response=20
  <P>HTTP/1.1 207 Multi-Status <BR>Content-Type: text/xml; =
charset=3D"utf-8"=20
  <BR>Content-Length: xxxx=20
  <P><PRE>      &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
      &lt;d:multistatus xmlns:d=3D"DAV:"&gt;
        &lt;d:response&gt;
             &lt;d:href&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/othercontainer/R2/</d:href">http://www.foo.bar=
/othercontainer/R2/</D:HREF< a>&gt;
             &lt;d:status&gt;HTTP/1.1 412 Precondition =
Failed&lt;/d:status&gt;
        &lt;/d:response&gt;
      &lt;/d:multistatus&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>The Depth header is unnecessary as the default behavior of COPY on =
a=20
  collection is to act as if a "Depth: infinity" header had been =
submitted. In=20
  this example most of the resources, along with the collection, were =
copied=20
  successfully. However the collection R2 failed, most likely due to a =
problem=20
  with maintaining the liveness of properties (this is specified by the=20
  propertybehavior XML element). Because there was an error copying R2, =
none of=20
  R2's members were copied. However no errors were listed for those =
members due=20
  to the error minimization rules given in section 8.8.3.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-42>Page 42</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.9>8.9</A> MOVE Method</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The MOVE operation on a non-collection resource is the logical =
equivalent=20
  of a copy (COPY), followed by consistency maintenance processing, =
followed by=20
  a delete of the source, where all three actions are performed =
atomically. The=20
  consistency maintenance step allows the server to perform updates =
caused by=20
  the move, such as updating all URIs other than the Request-URI which =
identify=20
  the source resource, to point to the new destination resource. =
Consequently,=20
  the Destination header <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be present on all MOVE =
methods=20
  and <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> follow all COPY requirements for the COPY =
part of=20
  the MOVE method. All DAV compliant resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> =
support the=20
  MOVE method. However, support for the MOVE method does not guarantee =
the=20
  ability to move a resource to a particular destination.=20
  <P>For example, separate programs may actually control different sets =
of=20
  resources on the same server. Therefore, it may not be possible to =
move a=20
  resource within a namespace that appears to belong to the same server. =

  <P>If a resource exists at the destination, the destination resource =
will be=20
  DELETEd as a side-effect of the MOVE operation, subject to the =
restrictions of=20
  the Overwrite header.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.9.1>8.9.1</A> MOVE for Properties</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The behavior of properties on a MOVE, including the effects of the=20
  propertybehavior XML element, <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be the same as =
specified=20
  in section 8.8.2.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.9.2>8.9.2</A> MOVE for =
Collections</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A MOVE with "Depth: infinity" instructs that the collection =
identified by=20
  the Request-URI be moved to the URI specified in the Destination =
header, and=20
  all resources identified by its internal member URIs are to be moved =
to=20
  locations relative to it, recursively through all levels of the =
collection=20
  hierarchy.=20
  <P>The MOVE method on a collection <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> act as if a =
"Depth:=20
  infinity" header was used on it. A client <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> =
submit a=20
  Depth header on a MOVE on a collection with any value but "infinity".=20
  <P>Any headers included with MOVE <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be applied in=20
  processing every resource to be moved with the exception of the =
Destination=20
  header.=20
  <P>The behavior of the Destination header is the same as given for =
COPY on=20
  collections.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-43>Page 43</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>When the MOVE method has completed processing it =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG> have=20
  created a consistent namespace at both the source and destination (see =
section=20
  5.1 for the definition of namespace consistency). However, if an error =
occurs=20
  while moving an internal collection, the server <STRONG>MUST =
NOT</STRONG> move=20
  any resources identified by members of the failed collection (i.e., =
the server=20
  must skip the error-causing subtree), as this would create an =
inconsistent=20
  namespace. In this case, after detecting the error, the move operation =

  <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> try to finish as much of the original move as =
possible=20
  (i.e., the server should still attempt to move other subtrees and the=20
  resources identified by their members, that are not descendents of an=20
  error-causing collection). So, for example, if an infinite depth move =
is=20
  performed on collection /a/, which contains collections /a/b/ and =
/a/c/, and=20
  an error occurs moving /a/b/, an attempt should still be made to try =
moving=20
  /a/c/. Similarly, after encountering an error moving a non-collection =
resource=20
  as part of an infinite depth move, the server <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> =
try to=20
  finish as much of the original move operation as possible.=20
  <P>If an error occurs with a resource other than the resource =
identified in=20
  the Request-URI then the response <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be a 207=20
  (Multi-Status).=20
  <P>The 424 (Failed Dependency) status code <STRONG>SHOULD NOT</STRONG> =
be=20
  returned in the 207 (Multi-Status) response from a MOVE method. These =
errors=20
  can be safely omitted because the client will know that the progeny of =
a=20
  resource could not be moved when the client receives an error for the =
parent.=20
  Additionally 201 (Created)/204 (No Content) responses =
<STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG>=20
  NOT be returned as values in 207 (Multi-Status) responses from a MOVE. =
These=20
  responses can be safely omitted because they are the default success =
codes.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.9.3>8.9.3</A> MOVE and the Overwrite =
Header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>If a resource exists at the destination and the Overwrite header is =
"T"=20
  then prior to performing the move the server <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> =
perform a=20
  DELETE with "Depth: infinity" on the destination resource. If the =
Overwrite=20
  header is set to "F" then the operation will fail.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.9.4>8.9.4</A> Status Codes</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>201 (Created) - The source resource was successfully moved, and a =
new=20
  resource was created at the destination.=20
  <P>204 (No Content) - The source resource was successfully moved to a=20
  pre-existing destination resource.=20
  <P>403 (Forbidden) _ The source and destination URIs are the same.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-44>Page 44</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>409 (Conflict) _ A resource cannot be created at the destination =
until one=20
  or more intermediate collections have been created.=20
  <P>412 (Precondition Failed) - The server was unable to maintain the =
liveness=20
  of the properties listed in the propertybehavior XML element or the =
Overwrite=20
  header is "F" and the state of the destination resource is non-null.=20
  <P>423 (Locked) - The source or the destination resource was locked.=20
  <P>502 (Bad Gateway) - This may occur when the destination is on =
another=20
  server and the destination server refuses to accept the resource.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.9.5>8.9.5</A> Example - MOVE of a=20
  Non-Collection</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>This example shows resource <BR><A=20
