  <P>This example shows a request for an exclusive write lock on a =
collection=20
  and all its children. In this request, the client has specified that =
it=20
  desires an infinite length lock, if available, otherwise a timeout of =
4.1=20
  billion seconds, if available. The request entity body contains the =
contact=20
  information for the principal taking out the lock, in this case a web =
page=20
  URL.=20
  <P>The error is a 403 (Forbidden) response on the resource <BR><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://webdav.sb.aol.com/webdav/secret">http://webdav.sb.aol.com/=
webdav/secret</A>.=20
  Because this resource could not be locked, none of the resources were =
locked.=20
  Note also that the lockdiscovery property for the Request-URI has been =

  included as required. In this example the lockdiscovery property is =
empty=20
  which means that there are no outstanding locks on the resource.=20
  <P>In this example, the nonce, response, and opaque fields have not =
been=20
  calculated in the Authorization request header.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.11>8.11</A> UNLOCK Method</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The UNLOCK method removes the lock identified by the lock token in =
the=20
  Lock-Token request header from the Request-URI, and all other =
resources=20
  included in the lock. If all resources which have been locked under =
the=20
  submitted lock token can not be unlocked then the UNLOCK request=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> fail.=20
  <P>Any DAV compliant resource which supports the LOCK method=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the UNLOCK method.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-52>Page 52</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-8.11.1>8.11.1</A> Example - UNLOCK</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Request=20
  <P>UNLOCK /workspace/webdav/info.doc HTTP/1.1 <BR>Host: =
webdav.sb.aol.com=20
  <BR>Lock-Token: =
&lt;opaquelocktoken:a515cfa4-5da4-22e1-f5b5-00a0451e6bf7&gt;=20
  Authorization: Digest username=3D"ejw", =
<BR>realm=3D"ejw@webdav.sb.aol.com",=20
  nonce=3D"...", <BR>uri=3D"/workspace/webdav/proposal.doc", =
<BR>response=3D"...",=20
  opaque=3D"..."=20
  <P>&gt;&gt;Response=20
  <P>HTTP/1.1 204 No Content=20
  <P>In this example, the lock identified by the lock token=20
  <BR>"opaquelocktoken:a515cfa4-5da4-22e1-f5b5-00a0451e6bf7" is =
successfully=20
  removed from the resource <BR><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://webdav.sb.aol.com/workspace/webdav/info.doc">http://webdav=
.sb.aol.com/workspace/webdav/info.doc</A>.=20
  If this lock included more than just one resource, the lock is removed =
from=20
  all resources included in the lock. The 204 (No Content) status code =
is used=20
  instead of 200 (OK) because there is no response entity body.=20
  <P>In this example, the nonce, response, and opaque fields have not =
been=20
  calculated in the Authorization request header.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9>9</A> HTTP Headers for Distributed=20
Authoring</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.1>9.1</A> DAV Header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>DAV =3D "DAV" ":" "1" ["," "2"] ["," 1#extend]=20
  <P>This header indicates that the resource supports the DAV schema and =

  protocol as specified. All DAV compliant resources =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG>=20
  return the DAV header on all OPTIONS responses.=20
  <P>The value is a list of all compliance classes that the resource =
supports.=20
  Note that above a comma has already been added to the 2. This is =
because a=20
  resource can not be level 2 compliant unless it is also level 1 =
compliant.=20
  Please refer to section 15 for more details. In general, however, =
support for=20
  one compliance class does not entail support for any other.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.2>9.2</A> Depth Header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Depth =3D "Depth" ":" ("0" | "1" | "infinity")=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-53>Page 53</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>The Depth header is used with methods executed on resources which =
could=20
  potentially have internal members to indicate whether the method is to =
be=20
  applied only to the resource ("Depth: 0"), to the resource and its =
immediate=20
  children, ("Depth: 1"), or the resource and all its progeny ("Depth:=20
  infinity").=20
  <P>The Depth header is only supported if a method's definition =
explicitly=20
  provides for such support.=20
  <P>The following rules are the default behavior for any method that =
supports=20
  the Depth header. A method may override these defaults by defining =
different=20
  behavior in its definition.=20
  <P>Methods which support the Depth header may choose not to support =
all of the=20
  header's values and may define, on a case by case basis, the behavior =
of the=20
  method if a Depth header is not present. For example, the MOVE method =
only=20
  supports "Depth: infinity" and if a Depth header is not present will =
act as if=20
  a "Depth: infinity" header had been applied.=20
  <P>Clients <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> rely upon methods executing on =
members of=20
  their hierarchies in any particular order or on the execution being =
atomic=20
  unless the particular method explicitly provides such guarantees.=20
  <P>Upon execution, a method with a Depth header will perform as much =
of its=20
  assigned task as possible and then return a response specifying what =
it was=20
  able to accomplish and what it failed to do.=20
  <P>So, for example, an attempt to COPY a hierarchy may result in some =
of the=20
  members being copied and some not.=20
  <P>Any headers on a method that has a defined interaction with the =
Depth=20
  header <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be applied to all resources in the scope =
of the=20
  method except where alternative behavior is explicitly defined. For =
example,=20
  an If-Match header will have its value applied against every resource =
in the=20
  method's scope and will cause the method to fail if the header fails =
to match.=20

  <P>If a resource, source or destination, within the scope of the =
method with a=20
  Depth header is locked in such a way as to prevent the successful =
execution of=20
  the method, then the lock token for that resource =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be=20
  submitted with the request in the If request header.=20
  <P>The Depth header only specifies the behavior of the method with =
regards to=20
  internal children. If a resource does not have internal children then =
the=20
  Depth header <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be ignored.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-54>Page 54</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>Please note, however, that it is always an error to submit a value =
for the=20
  Depth header that is not allowed by the method's definition. Thus =
submitting a=20
  "Depth: 1" on a COPY, even if the resource does not have internal =
members,=20
  will result in a 400 (Bad Request). The method should fail not because =
the=20
  resource doesn't have internal members, but because of the illegal =
value in=20
  the header.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.3>9.3</A> Destination Header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Destination =3D "Destination" ":" absoluteURI=20
  <P>The Destination header specifies the URI which identifies a =
destination=20
  resource for methods such as COPY and MOVE, which take two URIs as =
parameters.=20
  Note that the absoluteURI production is defined in [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2396.html">RFC2396</A>].=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.4>9.4</A> If Header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>If =3D "If" ":" ( 1*No-tag-list | 1*Tagged-list) <BR>No-tag-list =
=3D List=20
  <BR>Tagged-list =3D Resource 1*List <BR>Resource =3D Coded-URL =
<BR>List =3D "("=20
  1*(["Not"](State-token | "[" entity-tag "]")) ")" State-token =3D =
Coded-URL=20
  <BR>Coded-URL =3D "&lt;" absoluteURI "&gt;"=20
  <P>The If header is intended to have similar functionality to the If- =
Match=20
  header defined in section 14.25 of [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2068.html">RFC2068</A>]. =
However=20
  the If header is intended for use with any URI which represents state=20
  information, referred to as a state token, about a resource as well as =
ETags.=20
  A typical example of a state token is a lock token, and lock tokens =
are the=20
  only state tokens defined in this specification.=20
  <P>All DAV compliant resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> honor the If =
header.=20
  <P>The If header's purpose is to describe a series of state lists. If =
the=20
  state of the resource to which the header is applied does not match =
any of the=20
  specified state lists then the request <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> fail with =
a 412=20
  (Precondition Failed). If one of the described state lists matches the =
state=20
  of the resource then the request may succeed.=20
  <P>Note that the absoluteURI production is defined in [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2396.html">RFC2396</A>].=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-55>Page 55</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.4.1>9.4.1</A> No-tag-list =
Production</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The No-tag-list production describes a series of state tokens and =
ETags. If=20
  multiple No-tag-list productions are used then one only needs to match =
the=20
  state of the resource for the method to be allowed to continue.=20
  <P>If a method, due to the presence of a Depth or Destination header, =
is=20
  applied to multiple resources then the No-tag-list production=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be applied to each resource the method is =
applied to.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.4.1.1>9.4.1.1</A> Example - No-tag-list If =

  Header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>If: (&lt;locktoken:a-write-lock-token&gt; ["I am an ETag"]) (["I am =
another=20
  ETag"])=20
  <P>The previous header would require that any resources within the =
scope of=20
  the method must either be locked with the specified lock token and in =
the=20
  state identified by the "I am an ETag" ETag or in the state identified =
by the=20
  second ETag "I am another ETag". To put the matter more plainly one =
can think=20
  of the previous If header as being in the form (or (and=20
  &lt;locktoken:a-write-lock-token&gt; ["I am an ETag"]) (and ["I am =
another=20
  ETag"])).=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.4.2>9.4.2</A> Tagged-list =
Production</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The tagged-list production scopes a list production. That is, it =
specifies=20
  that the lists following the resource specification only apply to the=20
  specified resource. The scope of the resource production begins with =
the list=20
  production immediately following the resource production and ends with =
the=20
  next resource production, if any.=20
  <P>When the If header is applied to a particular resource, the Tagged- =
list=20
  productions <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be searched to determine if any of =
the=20
  listed resources match the operand resource(s) for the current method. =
If none=20
  of the resource productions match the current resource then the header =

  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be ignored. If one of the resource productions =
does=20
  match the name of the resource under consideration then the list =
productions=20
  following the resource production <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be applied to =
the=20
  resource in the manner specified in the previous section.=20
  <P>The same URI <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> appear more than once in a =
resource=20
  production in an If header.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-56>Page 56</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.4.2.1>9.4.2.1</A> Example - Tagged List If =

  header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>COPY /resource1 HTTP/1.1 <BR>Host: www.foo.bar <BR>Destination: <A=20
  href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/resource2">http://www.foo.bar/resource2</A> =
<BR>If:=20
  &lt;<A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/resource1">http://www.foo.bar/resource1</A>&gt=
;=20
  (&lt;locktoken:a-write-lock-token&gt; [W/"A weak ETag"]) (["strong =
ETag"]) <PRE>   &lt;<A =
href=3D"http://www.bar.bar/random">http://www.bar.bar/random</A>&gt;(["an=
other strong ETag"])
</PRE>
  <P>In this example <A=20
  href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/resource1">http://www.foo.bar/resource1</A> =
is being=20
  copied to <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/resource2">http://www.foo.bar/resource2</A>. =
When the=20
  method is first applied to <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/resource1">http://www.foo.bar/resource1</A>,=20
  resource1 must be in the state specified by=20
  "(&lt;locktoken:a-write-lock-token&gt; [W/"A weak ETag"]) (["strong =
ETag"])",=20
  that is, it either must be locked with a lock token of=20
  "locktoken:a-write-lock-token" and have a weak entity tag W/"A weak =
ETag" or=20
  it must have a strong entity tag "strong ETag".=20
  <P>That is the only success condition since the resource <BR><A=20
  href=3D"http://www.bar.bar/random">http://www.bar.bar/random</A> never =
has the=20
  method applied to it (the only other resource listed in the If header) =
and=20
  <BR><A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/resource2">http://www.foo.bar/resource2</A> =
is=20
  not listed in the If header.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.4.3>9.4.3</A> not Production</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Every state token or ETag is either current, and hence describes =
the state=20
  of a resource, or is not current, and does not describe the state of a =

  resource. The boolean operation of matching a state token or ETag to =
the=20
  current state of a resource thus resolves to a true or false value. =
The not=20
  production is used to reverse that value. The scope of the not =
production is=20
  the state-token or entity-tag immediately following it.=20
  <P>If: (Not &lt;locktoken:write1&gt; &lt;locktoken:write2&gt;)=20
  <P>When submitted with a request, this If header requires that all =
operand=20
  resources must not be locked with locktoken:write1 and must be locked =
with=20
  locktoken:write2.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.4.4>9.4.4</A> Matching Function</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>When performing If header processing, the definition of a matching =
state=20
  token or entity tag is as follows.=20
  <P>Matching entity tag: Where the entity tag matches an entity tag =
associated=20
  with that resource.=20
  <P>Matching state token: Where there is an exact match between the =
state token=20
  in the If header and any state token on the resource.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-57>Page 57</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.4.5>9.4.5</A> If Header and Non-DAV =
Compliant=20
  Proxies</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Non-DAV compliant proxies will not honor the If header, since they =
will not=20
  understand the If header, and HTTP requires non-understood headers to =
be=20
  ignored. When communicating with HTTP/1.1 proxies, the "Cache-Control: =

  no-cache" request header <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be used so as to =
prevent the=20
  proxy from improperly trying to service the request from its cache. =
When=20
  dealing with HTTP/1.0 proxies the "Pragma: no-cache" request header=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be used for the same reason.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.5>9.5</A> Lock-Token Header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Lock-Token =3D "Lock-Token" ":" Coded-URL=20
  <P>The Lock-Token request header is used with the UNLOCK method to =
identify=20
  the lock to be removed. The lock token in the Lock-Token request =
header=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> identify a lock that contains the resource =
identified by=20
  Request-URI as a member.=20
  <P>The Lock-Token response header is used with the LOCK method to =
indicate the=20
  lock token created as a result of a successful LOCK request to create =
a new=20
  lock.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.6>9.6</A> Overwrite Header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Overwrite =3D "Overwrite" ":" ("T" | "F")=20
  <P>The Overwrite header specifies whether the server should overwrite =
the=20
  state of a non-null destination resource during a COPY or MOVE. A =
value of "F"=20
  states that the server must not perform the COPY or MOVE operation if =
the=20
  state of the destination resource is non-null. If the overwrite header =
is not=20
  included in a COPY or MOVE request then the resource =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG>=20
  treat the request as if it has an overwrite header of value "T". While =
the=20
  Overwrite header appears to duplicate the functionality of the =
If-Match: *=20
  header of HTTP/1.1, If-Match applies only to the Request-URI, and not =
to the=20
  Destination of a COPY or MOVE.=20
  <P>If a COPY or MOVE is not performed due to the value of the =
Overwrite=20
  header, the method <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> fail with a 412 (Precondition =
Failed)=20
  status code.=20
  <P>All DAV compliant resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the =
Overwrite=20
  header.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.7>9.7</A> Status-URI Response =
Header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The Status-URI response header may be used with the 102 =
(Processing) status=20
  code to inform the client as to the status of a method.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-58>Page 58</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>Status-URI =3D "Status-URI" ":" *(Status-Code Coded-URL) ; =
Status-Code is=20
  defined in 6.1.1 of [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2068.html">RFC2068</A>]=20
  <P>The URIs listed in the header are source resources which have been =
affected=20
  by the outstanding method. The status code indicates the resolution of =
the=20
  method on the identified resource. So, for example, if a MOVE method =
on a=20
  collection is outstanding and a 102 (Processing) response with a =
Status-URI=20
  response header is returned, the included URIs will indicate resources =
that=20
  have had move attempted on them and what the result was.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-9.8>9.8</A> Timeout Request Header</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>TimeOut =3D "Timeout" ":" 1#TimeType <BR>TimeType =3D ("Second-" =
DAVTimeOutVal=20
  | "Infinite" | Other) DAVTimeOutVal =3D 1*digit <PRE>   Other =3D =
"Extend" field-value   ; See section 4.2 of [RFC2068]
</PRE>
  <P>Clients may include Timeout headers in their LOCK requests. =
However, the=20
  server is not required to honor or even consider these requests. =
Clients=20
  <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> submit a Timeout request header with any =
method=20
  other than a LOCK method.=20
  <P>A Timeout request header <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> contain at least one =

  TimeType and may contain multiple TimeType entries. The purpose of =
listing=20
  multiple TimeType entries is to indicate multiple different values and =
value=20
  types that are acceptable to the client. The client lists the TimeType =
entries=20
  in order of preference.=20
  <P>Timeout response values <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> use a Second value, =
Infinite,=20
  or a TimeType the client has indicated familiarity with. The server =
may assume=20
  a client is familiar with any TimeType submitted in a Timeout header.=20
  <P>The "Second" TimeType specifies the number of seconds that will =
elapse=20
  between granting of the lock at the server, and the automatic removal =
of the=20
  lock. The timeout value for TimeType "Second" <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> =
NOT be=20
  greater than 2^32-1.=20
  <P>The timeout counter <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> be restarted any time =
an owner=20
  of the lock sends a method to any member of the lock, including =
unsupported=20
  methods, or methods which are unsuccessful. However the lock=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be refreshed if a refresh LOCK method is =
successfully=20
  received.=20
  <P>If the timeout expires then the lock may be lost. Specifically, if =
the=20
  server wishes to harvest the lock upon time-out, the server=20
  <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> act as if an UNLOCK method was executed by the =
server=20
  on the resource using the lock token of the timed-out lock, performed =
with=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-59>Page 59</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>its override authority. Thus logs should be updated with the =
disposition of=20
  the lock, notifications should be sent, etc., just as they would be =
for an=20
  UNLOCK request.=20
  <P>Servers are advised to pay close attention to the values submitted =
by=20
  clients, as they will be indicative of the type of activity the client =
intends=20
  to perform. For example, an applet running in a browser may need to =
lock a=20
  resource, but because of the instability of the environment within =
which the=20
  applet is running, the applet may be turned off without warning. As a =
result,=20
  the applet is likely to ask for a relatively small timeout value so =
that if=20
  the applet dies, the lock can be quickly harvested. However, a =
document=20
  management system is likely to ask for an extremely long timeout =
because its=20
  user may be planning on going off-line.=20
  <P>A client <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> assume that just because the =
time-out=20
  has expired the lock has been lost.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-10>10</A> Status Code Extensions to =
HTTP/1.1</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The following status codes are added to those defined in HTTP/1.1 =
[<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2068.html">RFC2068</A>].=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-10.1>10.1</A> 102 Processing</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The 102 (Processing) status code is an interim response used to =
inform the=20
  client that the server has accepted the complete request, but has not =
yet=20
  completed it. This status code <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> only be sent =
when the=20
  server has a reasonable expectation that the request will take =
significant=20
  time to complete. As guidance, if a method is taking longer than 20 =
seconds (a=20
  reasonable, but arbitrary value) to process the server =
<STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG>=20
  return a 102 (Processing) response. The server <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> =
send a=20
  final response after the request has been completed.=20
  <P>Methods can potentially take a long period of time to process, =
especially=20
  methods that support the Depth header. In such cases the client may =
time-out=20
  the connection while waiting for a response. To prevent this the =
server may=20
  return a 102 (Processing) status code to indicate to the client that =
the=20
  server is still processing the method.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-10.2>10.2</A> 207 Multi-Status</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The 207 (Multi-Status) status code provides status for multiple =
independent=20
  operations (see section 11 for more information).=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-60>Page 60</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-10.3>10.3</A> 422 Unprocessable =
Entity</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The 422 (Unprocessable Entity) status code means the server =
understands the=20
  content type of the request entity (hence a 415(Unsupported Media =
Type) status=20
  code is inappropriate), and the syntax of the request entity is =
correct (thus=20
  a 400 (Bad Request) status code is inappropriate) but was unable to =
process=20
  the contained instructions. For example, this error condition may =
occur if an=20
  XML request body contains well-formed (i.e., syntactically correct), =
but=20
  semantically erroneous XML instructions.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-10.4>10.4</A> 423 Locked</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The 423 (Locked) status code means the source or destination =
resource of a=20
  method is locked.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-10.5>10.5</A> 424 Failed Dependency</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The 424 (Failed Dependency) status code means that the method could =
not be=20
  performed on the resource because the requested action depended on =
another=20
  action and that action failed. For example, if a command in a =
PROPPATCH method=20
  fails then, at minimum, the rest of the commands will also fail with =
424=20
  (Failed Dependency).=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-10.6>10.6</A> 507 Insufficient =
Storage</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The 507 (Insufficient Storage) status code means the method could =
not be=20
  performed on the resource because the server is unable to store the=20
  representation needed to successfully complete the request. This =
condition is=20
  considered to be temporary. If the request which received this status =
code was=20
  the result of a user action, the request <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> be =
repeated=20
  until it is requested by a separate user action.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-11>11</A> Multi-Status Response</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The default 207 (Multi-Status) response body is a text/xml or=20
  application/xml HTTP entity that contains a single XML element called=20
  multistatus, which contains a set of XML elements called response =
which=20
  contain 200, 300, 400, and 500 series status codes generated during =
the method=20
  invocation. 100 series status codes <STRONG>SHOULD NOT</STRONG> be =
recorded in=20
  a response XML element.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-61>Page 61</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12>12</A> XML Element Definitions</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>In the section below, the final line of each section gives the =
element type=20
  declaration using the format defined in [REC-XML]. The "Value" field, =
where=20
  present, specifies further restrictions on the allowable contents of =
the XML=20
  element using BNF (i.e., to further restrict the values of a PCDATA =
element).=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.1>12.1</A> activelock XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       activelock
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Describes a lock on a resource.

   &lt;!ELEMENT activelock (lockscope, locktype, depth, owner?, =
timeout?,
   locktoken?) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.1.1>12.1.1</A> depth XML Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       depth
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    The value of the Depth header.
   Value:      "0" | "1" | "infinity"

   &lt;!ELEMENT depth (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.1.2>12.1.2</A> locktoken XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       locktoken
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    The lock token associated with a lock.
   Description: The href contains one or more opaque lock token URIs
   which all refer to the same lock (i.e., the OpaqueLockToken-URI
   production in section 6.4).

   &lt;!ELEMENT locktoken (href+) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.1.3>12.1.3</A> timeout XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       timeout
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    The timeout associated with a lock
   Value:      TimeType ;Defined in section 9.8

   &lt;!ELEMENT timeout (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-62>Page 62</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.2>12.2</A> collection XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       collection
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Identifies the associated resource as a collection. The
   resourcetype property of a collection resource <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> =
have this value.

   &lt;!ELEMENT collection EMPTY &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.3>12.3</A> href XML Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       href
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Identifies the content of the element as a URI.
   Value:      URI ; See section 3.2.1 of [RFC2068]

   &lt;!ELEMENT href (#PCDATA)&gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.4>12.4</A> link XML Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       link
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Identifies the property as a link and contains the source
   and destination of that link.
   Description: The link XML element is used to provide the sources and
   destinations of a link.  The name of the property containing the link
   XML element provides the type of the link.  Link is a multi-valued
   element, so multiple links may be used together to indicate multiple
   links with the same type.  The values in the href XML elements inside
   the src and dst XML elements of the link XML element <STRONG>MUST =
NOT</STRONG> be
   rejected if they point to resources which do not exist.

   &lt;!ELEMENT link (src+, dst+) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.4.1>12.4.1</A> dst XML Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       dst
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Indicates the destination of a link
   Value:      URI

   &lt;!ELEMENT dst (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.4.2>12.4.2</A> src XML Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       src
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Indicates the source of a link.
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-63>Page 63</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Value:      URI

   &lt;!ELEMENT src (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.5>12.5</A> lockentry XML Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       lockentry
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Defines the types of locks that can be used with the
   resource.

   &lt;!ELEMENT lockentry (lockscope, locktype) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.6>12.6</A> lockinfo XML Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       lockinfo
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    The lockinfo XML element is used with a LOCK method to
   specify the type of lock the client wishes to have created.

   &lt;!ELEMENT lockinfo (lockscope, locktype, owner?) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.7>12.7</A> lockscope XML Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       lockscope
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Specifies whether a lock is an exclusive lock, or a
   shared lock.

   &lt;!ELEMENT lockscope (exclusive | shared) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.7.1>12.7.1</A> exclusive XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       exclusive
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Specifies an exclusive lock

   &lt;!ELEMENT exclusive EMPTY &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.7.2>12.7.2</A> shared XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       shared
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Specifies a shared lock

   &lt;!ELEMENT shared EMPTY &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-64>Page 64</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.8>12.8</A> locktype XML Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       locktype
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Specifies the access type of a lock.  At present, this
   specification only defines one lock type, the write lock.

   &lt;!ELEMENT locktype (write) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.8.1>12.8.1</A> write XML Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       write
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Specifies a write lock.

   &lt;!ELEMENT write EMPTY &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.9>12.9</A> multistatus XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       multistatus
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Contains multiple response messages.
   Description: The responsedescription at the top level is used to
   provide a general message describing the overarching nature of the
   response.  If this value is available an application may use it
   instead of presenting the individual response descriptions contained
   within the responses.

   &lt;!ELEMENT multistatus (response+, responsedescription?) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.9.1>12.9.1</A> response XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       response
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Holds a single response describing the effect of a
   method on resource and/or its properties.
   Description: A particular href <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> appear more =
than once as the
   child of a response XML element under a multistatus XML element.
   This requirement is necessary in order to keep processing costs for a
   response to linear time.  Essentially, this prevents having to search
   in order to group together all the responses by href.  There are,
   however, no requirements regarding ordering based on href values.

   &lt;!ELEMENT response (href, ((href*, status)|(propstat+)),
   responsedescription?) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-65>Page 65</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.9.1.1>12.9.1.1</A> propstat XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       propstat
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Groups together a prop and status element that is
   associated with a particular href element.
   Description: The propstat XML element <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> contain =
one prop XML
   element and one status XML element.  The contents of the prop XML
   element <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> only list the names of properties to =
which the result in
   the status element applies.

   &lt;!ELEMENT propstat (prop, status, responsedescription?) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.9.1.2>12.9.1.2</A> status XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       status
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Holds a single HTTP status-line
   Value:      status-line   ;status-line defined in [RFC2068]

   &lt;!ELEMENT status (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.9.2>12.9.2</A> responsedescription XML=20
  Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       responsedescription
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Contains a message that can be displayed to the user
   explaining the nature of the response.
   Description: This XML element provides information suitable to be
   presented to a user.

   &lt;!ELEMENT responsedescription (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.10>12.10</A> owner XML Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       owner
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Provides information about the principal taking out a
   lock.
   Description: The owner XML element provides information sufficient
   for either directly contacting a principal (such as a telephone
   number or Email URI), or for discovering the principal (such as the
   URL of a homepage) who owns a lock.

   &lt;!ELEMENT owner ANY&gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-66>Page 66</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.11>12.11</A> prop XML element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       prop
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Contains properties related to a resource.
   Description: The prop XML element is a generic container for
   properties defined on resources.  All elements inside a prop XML
   element <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> define properties related to the =
resource.  No other
   elements may be used inside of a prop element.

   &lt;!ELEMENT prop ANY&gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.12>12.12</A> propertybehavior XML =
element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       propertybehavior Namespace:  DAV:  Purpose:    =
Specifies
   how properties are handled during a COPY or MOVE.
   Description: The propertybehavior XML element specifies how
   properties are handled during a COPY or MOVE.  If this XML element is
   not included in the request body then the server is expected to act
   as defined by the default property handling behavior of the
   associated method.  All WebDAV compliant resources =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the
   propertybehavior XML element.

   &lt;!ELEMENT propertybehavior (omit | keepalive) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.12.1>12.12.1</A> keepalive XML =
element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       keepalive
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Specifies requirements for the copying/moving of live
   properties.
   Description: If a list of URIs is included as the value of keepalive
   then the named properties <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be "live" after they =
are copied
   (moved) to the destination resource of a COPY (or MOVE).  If the
   value "*" is given for the keepalive XML element, this designates
   that all live properties on the source resource <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> =
be live on the
   destination.  If the requirements specified by the keepalive element
   can not be honored then the method <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> fail with a =
412 (Precondition
   Failed).  All DAV compliant resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support =
the keepalive XML
   element for use with the COPY and MOVE methods.
   Value:      "*" ; #PCDATA value can only be "*"

   &lt;!ELEMENT keepalive (#PCDATA | href+) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-67>Page 67</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.12.2>12.12.2</A> omit XML =
element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       omit
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    The omit XML element instructs the server that it should
   use best effort to copy properties but a failure to copy a property
   <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> cause the method to fail.  Description: The =
default behavior
   for a COPY or MOVE is to copy/move all properties or fail the method.
   In certain circumstances, such as when a server copies a resource
   over another protocol such as FTP, it may not be possible to
   copy/move the properties associated with the resource. Thus any
   attempt to copy/move over FTP would always have to fail because
   properties could not be moved over, even as dead properties.  All DAV
   compliant resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the omit XML =
element on COPY/MOVE
   methods.

   &lt;!ELEMENT omit EMPTY &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.13>12.13</A> propertyupdate XML =
element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       propertyupdate
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Contains a request to alter the properties on a
   resource.
   Description: This XML element is a container for the information
   required to modify the properties on the resource.  This XML element
   is multi-valued.

   &lt;!ELEMENT propertyupdate (remove | set)+ &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.13.1>12.13.1</A> remove XML =
element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       remove
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Lists the DAV properties to be removed from a resource.
   Description: Remove instructs that the properties specified in prop
   should be removed.  Specifying the removal of a property that does
   not exist is not an error.  All the XML elements in a prop XML
   element inside of a remove XML element <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be =
empty, as only the
   names of properties to be removed are required.

   &lt;!ELEMENT remove (prop) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.13.2>12.13.2</A> set XML element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       set
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Lists the DAV property values to be set for a resource.
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-68>Page 68</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>Description: The set XML element <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> contain only =
a prop=20
  XML element. The elements contained by the prop XML element inside the =
set XML=20
  element <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> specify the name and value of properties =
that=20
  are set on the resource identified by Request-URI. If a property =
already=20
  exists then its value is replaced. Language tagging information in the =

  property's value (in the "xml:lang" attribute, if present)=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be persistently stored along with the property, =
and=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be subsequently retrievable using PROPFIND.=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;!ELEMENT set (prop) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.14>12.14</A> propfind XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       propfind
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Specifies the properties to be returned from a PROPFIND
   method.  Two special elements are specified for use with propfind,
   allprop and propname.  If prop is used inside propfind it =
<STRONG>MUST</STRONG> only
   contain property names, not values.

   &lt;!ELEMENT propfind (allprop | propname | prop) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.14.1>12.14.1</A> allprop XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       allprop Namespace:  DAV:  Purpose:    The =
allprop XML
   element specifies that all property names and values on the resource
   are to be returned.

   &lt;!ELEMENT allprop EMPTY &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-12.14.2>12.14.2</A> propname XML =
Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       propname Namespace:  DAV:  Purpose:    The =
propname XML
   element specifies that only a list of property names on the resource
   is to be returned.

   &lt;!ELEMENT propname EMPTY &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13>13</A> DAV Properties</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>For DAV properties, the name of the property is also the same as =
the name=20
  of the XML element that contains its value. In the section below, the =
final=20
  line of each section gives the element type declaration using the =
format=20
  defined in [REC-XML]. The "Value" field, where present, specifies =
further=20
  restrictions on the allowable contents of the XML element using BNF =
(i.e., to=20
  further restrict the values of a PCDATA element).=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-69>Page 69</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.1>13.1</A> creationdate Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       creationdate
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Records the time and date the resource was created.
   Value:      date-time ; See Appendix 2
   Description: The creationdate property should be defined on all DAV
   compliant resources.  If present, it contains a timestamp of the
   moment when the resource was created (i.e., the moment it had non-
   null state).

   &lt;!ELEMENT creationdate (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.2>13.2</A> displayname Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       displayname
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Provides a name for the resource that is suitable for
   presentation to a user.
   Description: The displayname property should be defined on all DAV
   compliant resources.  If present, the property contains a description
   of the resource that is suitable for presentation to a user.

   &lt;!ELEMENT displayname (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.3>13.3</A> getcontentlanguage =
Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       getcontentlanguage
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Contains the Content-Language header returned by a GET
   without accept headers
   Description: The getcontentlanguage property <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be =
defined on any
   DAV compliant resource that returns the Content-Language header on a
   GET.
   Value:      language-tag   ;language-tag is defined in section 14.13
   of [RFC2068]

   &lt;!ELEMENT getcontentlanguage (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.4>13.4</A> getcontentlength =
Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       getcontentlength
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Contains the Content-Length header returned by a GET
   without accept headers.
   Description: The getcontentlength property <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be =
defined on any
   DAV compliant resource that returns the Content-Length header in
   response to a GET.
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-70>Page 70</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Value:      content-length ; see section 14.14 of [RFC2068]

   &lt;!ELEMENT getcontentlength (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.5>13.5</A> getcontenttype =
Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       getcontenttype
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Contains the Content-Type header returned by a GET
   without accept headers.
   Description: This getcontenttype property <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be =
defined on any DAV
   compliant resource that returns the Content-Type header in response
   to a GET.
   Value:      media-type   ; defined in section 3.7 of [RFC2068]

   &lt;!ELEMENT getcontenttype (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.6>13.6</A> getetag Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       getetag
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Contains the ETag header returned by a GET without
   accept headers.
   Description: The getetag property <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be defined on =
any DAV
   compliant resource that returns the Etag header.
   Value:      entity-tag  ; defined in section 3.11 of [RFC2068]

   &lt;!ELEMENT getetag (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.7>13.7</A> getlastmodified =
Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       getlastmodified
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Contains the Last-Modified header returned by a GET
   method without accept headers.
   Description: Note that the last-modified date on a resource may
   reflect changes in any part of the state of the resource, not
   necessarily just a change to the response to the GET method.  For
   example, a change in a property may cause the last-modified date to
   change. The getlastmodified property <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be defined =
on any DAV
   compliant resource that returns the Last-Modified header in response
   to a GET.
   Value:      HTTP-date  ; defined in section 3.3.1 of [RFC2068]

   &lt;!ELEMENT getlastmodified (#PCDATA) &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-71>Page 71</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.8>13.8</A> lockdiscovery =
Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       lockdiscovery
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Describes the active locks on a resource
   Description: The lockdiscovery property returns a listing of who has
   a lock, what type of lock he has, the timeout type and the time
   remaining on the timeout, and the associated lock token.  The server
   is free to withhold any or all of this information if the requesting
   principal does not have sufficient access rights to see the requested
   data.

   &lt;!ELEMENT lockdiscovery (activelock)* &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.8.1>13.8.1</A> Example - Retrieving the=20
  lockdiscovery Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Request=20
  <P>PROPFIND /container/ HTTP/1.1 <BR>Host: www.foo.bar =
<BR>Content-Length:=20
  xxxx <BR>Content-Type: text/xml; charset=3D"utf-8"=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:propfind xmlns:D=3D'DAV:'&gt;
     &lt;D:prop&gt;&lt;D:lockdiscovery/&gt;&lt;/D:prop&gt;
   &lt;/D:propfind&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Response=20
  <P>HTTP/1.1 207 Multi-Status <BR>Content-Type: text/xml; =
charset=3D"utf-8"=20
  <BR>Content-Length: xxxx=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:multistatus xmlns:D=3D'DAV:'&gt;
     &lt;D:response&gt;
          &lt;D:href&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/container/</D:href">http://www.foo.bar/contain=
er/</D:HREF< a>&gt;
          &lt;D:propstat&gt;
               &lt;D:prop&gt;
                    &lt;D:lockdiscovery&gt;
                         &lt;D:activelock&gt;
                              =
&lt;D:locktype&gt;&lt;D:write/&gt;&lt;/D:locktype&gt;
                              =
&lt;D:lockscope&gt;&lt;D:exclusive/&gt;&lt;/D:lockscope&gt;
                              &lt;D:depth&gt;0&lt;/D:depth&gt;
                              &lt;D:owner&gt;Jane Smith&lt;/D:owner&gt;
                              =
&lt;D:timeout&gt;Infinite&lt;/D:timeout&gt;
                              &lt;D:locktoken&gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-72>Page 72</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>                                   &lt;D:href&gt;
               opaquelocktoken:f81de2ad-7f3d-a1b2-4f3c-00a0c91a9d76
                                   &lt;/D:href&gt;
                              &lt;/D:locktoken&gt;
                         &lt;/D:activelock&gt;
                    &lt;/D:lockdiscovery&gt;
               &lt;/D:prop&gt;
               &lt;D:status&gt;HTTP/1.1 200 OK&lt;/D:status&gt;
          &lt;/D:propstat&gt;
     &lt;/D:response&gt;
   &lt;/D:multistatus&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>This resource has a single exclusive write lock on it, with an =
infinite=20
  timeout.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.9>13.9</A> resourcetype Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       resourcetype
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    Specifies the nature of the resource.
   Description: The resourcetype property <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be =
defined on all DAV
   compliant resources.  The default value is empty.

   &lt;!ELEMENT resourcetype ANY &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.10>13.10</A> source Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       source
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    The destination of the source link identifies the
   resource that contains the unprocessed source of the link's source.
   Description: The source of the link (src) is typically the URI of the
   output resource on which the link is defined, and there is typically
   only one destination (dst) of the link, which is the URI where the
   unprocessed source of the resource may be accessed.  When more than
   one link destination exists, this specification asserts no policy on
   ordering.

   &lt;!ELEMENT source (link)* &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.10.1>13.10.1</A> Example - A source=20
  Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:prop xmlns:D=3D"DAV:" xmlns:F=3D"<A =
href=3D"http://www.foocorp.com/Project/">http://www.foocorp.com/Project/<=
/A>"&gt;
     &lt;D:source&gt;
          &lt;D:link&gt;
               &lt;F:projfiles&gt;Source&lt;/F:projfiles&gt;
               &lt;D:src&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://foo.bar/program</D:src">http://foo.bar/program</D:SRC< =
a>&gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-73>Page 73</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>               &lt;D:dst&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://foo.bar/src/main.c</D:dst">http://foo.bar/src/main.c</D:DS=
T< a>&gt;
          &lt;/D:link&gt;
          &lt;D:link&gt;
               &lt;F:projfiles&gt;Library&lt;/F:projfiles&gt;
               &lt;D:src&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://foo.bar/program</D:src">http://foo.bar/program</D:SRC< =
a>&gt;
               &lt;D:dst&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://foo.bar/src/main.lib</D:dst">http://foo.bar/src/main.lib</=
D:DST< a>&gt;
          &lt;/D:link&gt;
          &lt;D:link&gt;
               &lt;F:projfiles&gt;Makefile&lt;/F:projfiles&gt;
               &lt;D:src&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://foo.bar/program</D:src">http://foo.bar/program</D:SRC< =
a>&gt;
               &lt;D:dst&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://foo.bar/src/makefile</D:dst">http://foo.bar/src/makefile</=
D:DST< a>&gt;
          &lt;/D:link&gt;
     &lt;/D:source&gt;
   &lt;/D:prop&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>In this example the resource <A=20
  href=3D"http://foo.bar/program">http://foo.bar/program</A> has a =
source property=20
  that contains three links. Each link contains three elements, two of =
which,=20
  src and dst, are part of the DAV schema defined in this document, and =
one=20
  which is defined by the schema <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.foocorp.com/project/">http://www.foocorp.com/project/<=
/A>=20
  (Source, Library, and Makefile). A client which only implements the =
elements=20
  in the DAV spec will not understand the foocorp elements and will =
ignore them,=20
  thus seeing the expected source and destination links. An enhanced =
client may=20
  know about the foocorp elements and be able to present the user with=20
  additional information about the links. This example demonstrates the =
power of=20
  XML markup, allowing element values to be enhanced without breaking =
older=20
  clients.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.11>13.11</A> supportedlock =
Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>   Name:       supportedlock
   Namespace:  DAV:
   Purpose:    To provide a listing of the lock capabilities supported
   by the resource.
   Description: The supportedlock property of a resource returns a
   listing of the combinations of scope and access types which may be
   specified in a lock request on the resource.  Note that the actual
   contents are themselves controlled by access controls so a server is
   not required to provide information the client is not authorized to
   see.

   &lt;!ELEMENT supportedlock (lockentry)* &gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-13.11.1>13.11.1</A> Example - Retrieving the =

  supportedlock Property</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Request=20
  <P>PROPFIND /container/ HTTP/1.1=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-74>Page 74</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>Host: www.foo.bar <BR>Content-Length: xxxx <BR>Content-Type: =
text/xml;=20
  charset=3D"utf-8"=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:propfind xmlns:D=3D"DAV:"&gt;
     &lt;D:prop&gt;&lt;D:supportedlock/&gt;&lt;/D:prop&gt;
   &lt;/D:propfind&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>&gt;&gt;Response=20
  <P>HTTP/1.1 207 Multi-Status <BR>Content-Type: text/xml; =
charset=3D"utf-8"=20
  <BR>Content-Length: xxxx=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:multistatus xmlns:D=3D"DAV:"&gt;
     &lt;D:response&gt;
          &lt;D:href&gt;<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/container/</D:href">http://www.foo.bar/contain=
er/</D:HREF< a>&gt;
          &lt;D:propstat&gt;
               &lt;D:prop&gt;
                    &lt;D:supportedlock&gt;
                         &lt;D:lockentry&gt;
                              =
&lt;D:lockscope&gt;&lt;D:exclusive/&gt;&lt;/D:lockscope&gt;
                              =
&lt;D:locktype&gt;&lt;D:write/&gt;&lt;/D:locktype&gt;
                         &lt;/D:lockentry&gt;
                         &lt;D:lockentry&gt;
                              =
&lt;D:lockscope&gt;&lt;D:shared/&gt;&lt;/D:lockscope&gt;
                              =
&lt;D:locktype&gt;&lt;D:write/&gt;&lt;/D:locktype&gt;
                         &lt;/D:lockentry&gt;
                    &lt;/D:supportedlock&gt;
               &lt;/D:prop&gt;
               &lt;D:status&gt;HTTP/1.1 200 OK&lt;/D:status&gt;
          &lt;/D:propstat&gt;
     &lt;/D:response&gt;
   &lt;/D:multistatus&gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-14>14</A> Instructions for Processing XML in =

  DAV</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>All DAV compliant resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> ignore any =
unknown XML=20
  element and all its children encountered while processing a DAV method =
that=20
  uses XML as its command language.=20
  <P>This restriction also applies to the processing, by clients, of DAV =

  property values where unknown XML elements <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> be =
ignored=20
  unless the property's schema declares otherwise.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-75>Page 75</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>This restriction does not apply to setting dead DAV properties on =
the=20
  server where the server <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> record unknown XML =
elements.=20
  <P>Additionally, this restriction does not apply to the use of XML =
where XML=20
  happens to be the content type of the entity body, for example, when =
used as=20
  the body of a PUT.=20
  <P>Since XML can be transported as text/xml or application/xml, a DAV =
server=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> accept DAV method requests with XML parameters=20
  transported as either text/xml or application/xml, and DAV client=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> accept XML responses using either text/xml or=20
  application/xml.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-15>15</A> DAV Compliance Classes</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A DAV compliant resource can choose from two classes of compliance. =
A=20
  client can discover the compliance classes of a resource by executing =
OPTIONS=20
  on the resource, and examining the "DAV" header which is returned.=20
  <P>Since this document describes extensions to the HTTP/1.1 protocol,=20
  minimally all DAV compliant resources, clients, and proxies=20
  <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> be compliant with [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2068.html">RFC2068</A>].=20
  <P>Compliance classes are not necessarily sequential. A resource that =
is class=20
  2 compliant must also be class 1 compliant; but if additional =
compliance=20
  classes are defined later, a resource that is class 1, 2, and 4 =
compliant=20
  might not be class 3 compliant. Also note that identifiers other than =
numbers=20
  may be used as compliance class identifiers.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-15.1>15.1</A> Class 1</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A class 1 compliant resource <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> meet all=20
  "<STRONG>MUST</STRONG>" requirements in all sections of this document. =

  <P>Class 1 compliant resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> return, at =
minimum, the=20
  value "1" in the DAV header on all responses to the OPTIONS method.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-15.2>15.2</A> Class 2</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A class 2 compliant resource <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> meet all class 1 =

  requirements and support the LOCK method, the supportedlock property, =
the=20
  <BR>lockdiscovery property, the Time-Out response header and the Lock- =
Token=20
  request header. A class "2" compliant resource <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> =
also=20
  support the Time-Out request header and the owner XML element.=20
  <P>Class 2 compliant resources <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> return, at =
minimum, the=20
  values "1" and "2" in the DAV header on all responses to the OPTIONS =
method.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-76>Page 76</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-16>16</A> Internationalization =
Considerations</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>In the realm of internationalization, this specification complies =
with the=20
  IETF Character Set Policy [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2277.html">RFC2277</A>]. =
In this=20
  specification, human-readable fields can be found either in the value =
of a=20
  property, or in an error message returned in a response entity body. =
In both=20
  cases, the human-readable content is encoded using XML, which has =
explicit=20
  provisions for character set tagging and encoding, and requires that =
XML=20
  processors read XML elements encoded, at minimum, using the UTF-8 =
[UTF-8]=20
  encoding of the ISO 10646 multilingual plane. XML examples in this=20
  specification demonstrate use of the charset parameter of the =
Content-Type=20
  header, as defined in [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2376.html">RFC2376</A>], =
as well as=20
  the XML "encoding" attribute, which together provide charset =
identification=20
  information for MIME and XML processors.=20
  <P>XML also provides a language tagging capability for specifying the =
language=20
  of the contents of a particular XML element. XML uses either IANA =
registered=20
  language tags (see [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc1766.html">RFC1766</A>]) =
or ISO 639=20
  language tags [ISO-639] in the "xml:lang" attribute of an XML element =
to=20
  identify the language of its content and attributes.=20
  <P>WebDAV applications <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the character set =

  tagging, character set encoding, and the language tagging =
functionality of the=20
  XML specification. Implementors of WebDAV applications are strongly =
encouraged=20
  to read "XML Media Types" [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2376.html">RFC2376</A>] =
for=20
  instruction on which MIME media type to use for XML transport, and on =
use of=20
  the charset parameter of the Content-Type header.=20
  <P>Names used within this specification fall into three categories: =
names of=20
  protocol elements such as methods and headers, names of XML elements, =
and=20
  names of properties. Naming of protocol elements follows the precedent =
of=20
  HTTP, using English names encoded in USASCII for methods and headers. =
Since=20
  these protocol elements are not visible to users, and are in fact =
simply long=20
  token identifiers, they do not need to support encoding in multiple =
character=20
  sets. Similarly, though the names of XML elements used in this=20
  <BR>specification are English names encoded in UTF-8, these names are =
not=20
  visible to the user, and hence do not need to support multiple =
character set=20
  encodings.=20
  <P>The name of a property defined on a resource is a URI. Although =
some=20
  applications (e.g., a generic property viewer) will display property =
URIs=20
  directly to their users, it is expected that the typical application =
will use=20
  a fixed set of properties, and will provide a mapping from the =
property name=20
  URI to a human-readable field when displaying the property name to a =
user. It=20
  is only in the case where=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-77>Page 77</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>the set of properties is not known ahead of time that an =
application need=20
  display a property name URI to a user. We recommend that applications =
provide=20
  human-readable property names wherever feasible.=20
  <P>For error reporting, we follow the convention of HTTP/1.1 status =
codes,=20
  including with each status code a short, English description of the =
code=20
  (e.g., 423 (Locked)). While the possibility exists that a poorly =
crafted user=20
  agent would display this message to a user, internationalized =
applications=20
  will ignore this message, and display an appropriate message in the =
user's=20
  language and character set.=20
  <P>Since interoperation of clients and servers does not require locale =

  information, this specification does not specify any mechanism for=20
  transmission of this information.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-17>17</A> Security Considerations</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>This section is provided to detail issues concerning security =
implications=20
  of which WebDAV applications need to be aware.=20
  <P>All of the security considerations of HTTP/1.1 (discussed in [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2068.html">RFC2068</A>]) =
and XML=20
  (discussed in [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2376.html">RFC2376</A>]) =
also apply=20
  to WebDAV. In addition, the security risks inherent in remote =
authoring=20
  require stronger authentication technology, introduce several new =
privacy=20
  concerns, and may increase the hazards from poor server design. These =
issues=20
  are detailed below.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-17.1>17.1</A> Authentication of =
Clients</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Due to their emphasis on authoring, WebDAV servers need to use=20
  authentication technology to protect not just access to a network =
resource,=20
  but the integrity of the resource as well. Furthermore, the =
introduction of=20
  locking functionality requires support for authentication.=20
  <P>A password sent in the clear over an insecure channel is an =
inadequate=20
  means for protecting the accessibility and integrity of a resource as =
the=20
  password may be intercepted. Since Basic authentication for HTTP/1.1 =
performs=20
  essentially clear text transmission of a password, Basic =
authentication=20
  <STRONG>MUST NOT</STRONG> be used to authenticate a WebDAV client to a =
server=20
  unless the connection is secure. Furthermore, a WebDAV server =
<STRONG>MUST=20
  NOT</STRONG> send Basic <BR>authentication credentials in a =
WWW-Authenticate=20
  header unless the connection is secure. Examples of secure connections =
include=20
  a Transport Layer Security (TLS) connection employing a strong cipher =
suite=20
  with mutual authentication of client and server, or a connection over =
a=20
  network which is physically secure, for example, an isolated network =
in a=20
  building with restricted access.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-78>Page 78</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>WebDAV applications <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the Digest =
authentication=20
  scheme [<A =
href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2069.html">RFC2069</A>].=20
  Since Digest authentication verifies that both parties to a =
communication know=20
  a shared secret, a password, without having to send that secret in the =
clear,=20
  Digest authentication avoids the security problems inherent in Basic=20
  authentication while providing a level of authentication which is =
useful in a=20
  wide range of scenarios.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-17.2>17.2</A> Denial of Service</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Denial of service attacks are of special concern to WebDAV servers. =
WebDAV=20
  plus HTTP enables denial of service attacks on every part of a =
system's=20
  resources.=20
  <P>The underlying storage can be attacked by PUTting extremely large =
files.=20
  <P>Asking for recursive operations on large collections can attack =
processing=20
  time.=20
  <P>Making multiple pipelined requests on multiple connections can =
attack=20
  network connections.=20
  <P>WebDAV servers need to be aware of the possibility of a denial of =
service=20
  attack at all levels.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-17.3>17.3</A> Security through =
Obscurity</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>WebDAV provides, through the PROPFIND method, a mechanism for =
listing the=20
  member resources of a collection. This greatly diminishes the =
effectiveness of=20
  security or privacy techniques that rely only on the difficulty of =
discovering=20
  the names of network resources. Users of WebDAV servers are encouraged =
to use=20
  access control techniques to prevent unwanted access to resources, =
rather than=20
  depending on the relative obscurity of their resource names.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-17.4>17.4</A> Privacy Issues Connected to=20
  Locks</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>When submitting a lock request a user agent may also submit an =
owner XML=20
  field giving contact information for the person taking out the lock =
(for those=20
  cases where a person, rather than a robot, is taking out the lock). =
This=20
  contact information is stored in a lockdiscovery property on the =
resource, and=20
  can be used by other collaborators to begin negotiation over access to =
the=20
  resource. However, in many cases this contact information can be very =
private,=20
  and should not be widely disseminated. Servers <STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> =
limit=20
  read access to the lockdiscovery property as appropriate. Furthermore, =
user=20
  agents=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-79>Page 79</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P><STRONG>SHOULD</STRONG> provide control over whether contact =
information is=20
  sent at all, and if contact information is sent, control over exactly =
what=20
  information is sent.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-17.5>17.5</A> Privacy Issues Connected to=20
  Properties</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Since property values are typically used to hold information such =
as the=20
  author of a document, there is the possibility that privacy concerns =
could=20
  arise stemming from widespread access to a resource's property data. =
To reduce=20
  the risk of inadvertent release of private information via properties, =
servers=20
  are encouraged to develop access control mechanisms that separate read =
access=20
  to the resource body and read access to the resource's properties. =
This allows=20
  a user to control the dissemination of their property data without =
overly=20
  restricting access to the resource's contents.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-17.6>17.6</A> Reduction of Security due to =
Source=20
  Link</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>HTTP/1.1 warns against providing read access to script code because =
it may=20
  contain sensitive information. Yet WebDAV, via its source link =
facility, can=20
  potentially provide a URI for script resources so they may be =
authored. For=20
  HTTP/1.1, a server could reasonably prevent access to source resources =
due to=20
  the predominance of read- only access. WebDAV, with its emphasis on =
authoring,=20
  encourages read and write access to source resources, and provides the =
source=20
  link facility to identify the source. This reduces the security =
benefits of=20
  eliminating access to source resources. Users and administrators of =
WebDAV=20
  servers should be very cautious when allowing remote authoring of =
scripts,=20
  limiting read and write access to the source resources to authorized=20
  principals.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-17.7>17.7</A> Implications of XML External=20
  Entities</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>XML supports a facility known as "external entities", defined in =
section=20
  4.2.2 of [REC-XML], which instruct an XML processor to retrieve and =
perform an=20
  inline include of XML located at a particular URI. An external XML =
entity can=20
  be used to append or modify the document type declaration (DTD) =
associated=20
  with an XML document. An external XML entity can also be used to =
include XML=20
  within the content of an XML document. For non-validating XML, such as =
the XML=20
  used in this specification, including an external XML entity is not =
required=20
  by [REC-XML]. However, [REC-XML] does state that an XML processor may, =
at its=20
  discretion, include the external XML entity.=20
  <P>External XML entities have no inherent trustworthiness and are =
subject to=20
  all the attacks that are endemic to any HTTP GET request. Furthermore, =
it is=20
  possible for an external XML entity to modify the DTD, and hence =
affect the=20
  final form of an XML document, in the worst=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-80>Page 80</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>case significantly modifying its semantics, or exposing the XML =
processor=20
  to the security risks discussed in [<A=20
  href=3D"http://andrew2.andrew.cmu.edu/rfc/rfc2376.html">RFC2376</A>]. =
Therefore,=20
  implementers must be aware that external XML entities should be =
treated as=20
  untrustworthy.=20
  <P>There is also the scalability risk that would accompany a widely =
deployed=20
  application which made use of external XML entities. In this =
situation, it is=20
  possible that there would be significant numbers of requests for one =
external=20
  XML entity, potentially overloading any server which fields requests =
for the=20
  resource containing the external XML entity.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-17.8>17.8</A> Risks Connected with Lock=20
Tokens</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>This specification, in section 6.4, requires the use of Universal =
Unique=20
  Identifiers (UUIDs) for lock tokens, in order to guarantee their =
uniqueness=20
  across space and time. UUIDs, as defined in [ISO- 11578], contain a =
"node"=20
  field which "consists of the IEEE address, usually the host address. =
For=20
  systems with multiple IEEE 802 nodes, any available node address can =
be used."=20
  Since a WebDAV server will issue many locks over its lifetime, the =
implication=20
  is that it will also be publicly exposing its IEEE 802 address.=20
  <P>There are several risks associated with exposure of IEEE 802 =
addresses.=20
  Using the IEEE 802 address:=20
  <P><PRE>   * It is possible to track the movement of hardware from =
subnet to
   subnet.

   * It may be possible to identify the manufacturer of the hardware
   running a WebDAV server.

   * It may be possible to determine the number of each type of computer
   running WebDAV.
</PRE>
  <P>Section 6.4.1 of this specification details an alternate mechanism =
for=20
  generating the "node" field of a UUID without using an IEEE 802 =
address, which=20
  alleviates the risks associated with exposure of IEEE 802 addresses by =
using=20
  an alternate source of uniqueness.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-18>18</A> IANA Considerations</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>This document defines two namespaces, the namespace of property =
names, and=20
  the namespace of WebDAV-specific XML elements used within property =
values.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-81>Page 81</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>URIs are used for both names, for several reasons. Assignment of a =
URI does=20
  not require a request to a central naming authority, and hence allow =
WebDAV=20
  property names and XML elements to be quickly defined by any WebDAV =
user or=20
  application. URIs also provide a unique address space, ensuring that =
the=20
  distributed users of WebDAV will not have collisions among the =
property names=20
  and XML elements they create.=20
  <P>This specification defines a distinguished set of property names =
and XML=20
  elements that are understood by all WebDAV applications. The property =
names=20
  and XML elements in this specification are all derived from the base =
URI DAV:=20
  by adding a suffix to this URI, for example, DAV:creationdate for the=20
  "creationdate" property.=20
  <P>This specification also defines a URI scheme for the encoding of =
lock=20
  tokens, the opaquelocktoken URI scheme described in section 6.4.=20
  <P>To ensure correct interoperation based on this specification, IANA =
must=20
  reserve the URI namespaces starting with "DAV:" and with =
"opaquelocktoken:"=20
  for use by this specification, its revisions, and related WebDAV=20
  specifications.=20
  <P></P>
