  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-23.2>23.2</A> Appendix 2 - ISO 8601 Date and =
Time=20
  Profile</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The creationdate property specifies the use of the ISO 8601 date =
format=20
  [ISO-8601]. This section defines a profile of the ISO 8601 date format =
for use=20
  with this specification. This profile is quoted from an Internet-Draft =
by=20
  Chris Newman, and is mentioned here to properly attribute his work.=20
  <P><PRE>   date-time       =3D full-date "T" full-time

   full-date       =3D date-fullyear "-" date-month "-" date-mday
   full-time       =3D partial-time time-offset

   date-fullyear   =3D 4DIGIT
   date-month      =3D 2DIGIT  ; 01-12
   date-mday       =3D 2DIGIT  ; 01-28, 01-29, 01-30, 01-31 based on
   month/year
   time-hour       =3D 2DIGIT  ; 00-23
   time-minute     =3D 2DIGIT  ; 00-59
   time-second     =3D 2DIGIT  ; 00-59, 00-60 based on leap second rules
   time-secfrac    =3D "." 1*DIGIT
   time-numoffset  =3D ("+" / "-") time-hour ":" time-minute
   time-offset     =3D "Z" / time-numoffset

   partial-time    =3D time-hour ":" time-minute ":" time-second
                    [time-secfrac]
</PRE>
  <P>Numeric offsets are calculated as local time minus UTC (Coordinated =

  Universal Time). So the equivalent time in UTC can be determined by=20
  subtracting the offset from the local time. For example, 18:50:00- =
04:00 is=20
  the same time as 22:58:00Z.=20
  <P>If the time in UTC is known, but the offset to local time is =
unknown, this=20
  can be represented with an offset of "-00:00". This differs from an =
offset of=20
  "Z" which implies that UTC is the preferred reference point for the =
specified=20
  time.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-89>Page 89</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-23.3>23.3</A> Appendix 3 - Notes on =
Processing XML=20
  Elements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-23.3.1>23.3.1</A> Notes on Empty XML =
Elements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>XML supports two mechanisms for indicating that an XML element does =
not=20
  have any content. The first is to declare an XML element of the form=20
  &lt;A&gt;&lt;/A&gt;. The second is to declare an XML element of the =
form <PRE>   &lt;A/&gt;.  The two XML elements are semantically =
identical.
</PRE>
  <P>It is a violation of the XML specification to use the =
&lt;A&gt;&lt;/A&gt;=20
  form if the associated DTD declares the element to be EMPTY (e.g.,=20
  &lt;!ELEMENT A EMPTY&gt;). If such a statement is included, then the =
empty=20
  element format, &lt;A/&gt; must be used. If the element is not =
declared to be=20
  EMPTY, then either form &lt;A&gt;&lt;/A&gt; or &lt;A/&gt; may be used =
for=20
  empty elements.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-23.3.2>23.3.2</A> Notes on Illegal XML=20
  Processing</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>XML is a flexible data format that makes it easy to submit data =
that=20
  appears legal but in fact is not. The philosophy of "Be flexible in =
what you=20
  accept and strict in what you send" still applies, but it must not be =
applied=20
  inappropriately. XML is extremely flexible in dealing with issues of =
white=20
  space, element ordering, inserting new elements, etc. This flexibility =
does=20
  not require extension, especially not in the area of the meaning of =
elements.=20
  <P>There is no kindness in accepting illegal combinations of XML =
elements. At=20
  best it will cause an unwanted result and at worst it can cause real =
damage.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-23.3.2.1>23.3.2.1</A> Example - XML Syntax=20
  Error</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The following request body for a PROPFIND method is illegal.=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:propfind xmlns:D=3D"DAV:"&gt;
     &lt;D:allprop/&gt;
     &lt;D:propname/&gt;
   &lt;/D:propfind&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>The definition of the propfind element only allows for the allprop =
or the=20
  propname element, not both. Thus the above is an error and must be =
responded=20
  to with a 400 (Bad Request).=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-90>Page 90</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>Imagine, however, that a server wanted to be "kind" and decided to =
pick the=20
  allprop element as the true element and respond to it. A client =
running over a=20
  bandwidth limited line who intended to execute a propname would be in =
for a=20
  big surprise if the server treated the command as an allprop.=20
  <P>Additionally, if a server were lenient and decided to reply to this =

  request, the results would vary randomly from server to server, with =
some=20
  servers executing the allprop directive, and others executing the =
propname=20
  directive. This reduces interoperability rather than increasing it.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-23.3.2.2>23.3.2.2</A> Example - Unknown XML=20
  Element</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The previous example was illegal because it contained two elements =
that=20
  were explicitly banned from appearing together in the propfind =
element.=20
  However, XML is an extensible language, so one can imagine new =
elements being=20
  defined for use with propfind. Below is the request body of a PROPFIND =
and,=20
  like the previous example, must be rejected with a 400 (Bad Request) =
by a=20
  server that does not understand the expired-props element.=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:propfind xmlns:D=3D"DAV:"
   xmlns:E=3D"<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/standards/props/">http://www.foo.bar/standards=
/props/</A>"&gt;
     &lt;E:expired-props/&gt;
   &lt;/D:propfind&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>To understand why a 400 (Bad Request) is returned let us look at =
the=20
  request body as the server unfamiliar with expired-props sees it.=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:propfind xmlns:D=3D"DAV:"
               xmlns:E=3D"<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/standards/props/">http://www.foo.bar/standards=
/props/</A>"&gt;
   &lt;/D:propfind&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>As the server does not understand the expired-props element, =
according to=20
  the WebDAV-specific XML processing rules specified in section 14, it =
must=20
  ignore it. Thus the server sees an empty propfind, which by the =
definition of=20
  the propfind element is illegal.=20
  <P>Please note that had the extension been additive it would not =
necessarily=20
  have resulted in a 400 (Bad Request). For example, imagine the =
following=20
  request body for a PROPFIND:=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"utf-8" ?&gt;
   &lt;D:propfind xmlns:D=3D"DAV:"
               xmlns:E=3D"<A =
href=3D"http://www.foo.bar/standards/props/">http://www.foo.bar/standards=
/props/</A>"&gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-91>Page 91</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P><PRE>     &lt;D:propname/&gt;
     &lt;E:leave-out&gt;*boss*&lt;/E:leave-out&gt;
   &lt;/D:propfind&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>The previous example contains the fictitious element leave-out. Its =
purpose=20
  is to prevent the return of any property whose name matches the =
submitted=20
  pattern. If the previous example were submitted to a server unfamiliar =
with=20
  leave-out, the only result would be that the leave-out element would =
be=20
  ignored and a propname would be executed.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-92>Page 92</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-23.4>23.4</A> Appendix 4 -- XML Namespaces =
for=20
  WebDAV</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-23.4.1>23.4.1</A> Introduction</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>All DAV compliant systems <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> support the XML =
namespace=20
  extensions as specified in [REC-XML-NAMES].=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-23.4.2>23.4.2</A> Meaning of Qualified =
Names</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>[Note to the reader: This section does not appear in =
[REC-XML-NAMES], but=20
  is necessary to avoid ambiguity for WebDAV XML processors.]=20
  <P>WebDAV compliant XML processors <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> interpret a =
qualified=20
  name as a URI constructed by appending the LocalPart to the namespace =
name=20
  URI.=20
  <P>Example=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;del:glider xmlns:del=3D"<A =
href=3D"http://www.del.jensen.org/">http://www.del.jensen.org/</A>"&gt;
     &lt;del:glidername&gt;
          Johnny Updraft
     &lt;/del:glidername&gt;
     &lt;del:glideraccidents/&gt;
   &lt;/del:glider&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>In this example, the qualified element name "del:glider" is =
interpreted as=20
  the URL "<A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.del.jensen.org/glider">http://www.del.jensen.org/glide=
r</A>".=20

  <P><PRE>   &lt;bar:glider xmlns:del=3D"<A =
href=3D"http://www.del.jensen.org/">http://www.del.jensen.org/</A>"&gt;
     &lt;bar:glidername&gt;
          Johnny Updraft
     &lt;/bar:glidername&gt;
     &lt;bar:glideraccidents/&gt;
   &lt;/bar:glider&gt;
</PRE>
  <P>Even though this example is syntactically different from the =
previous=20
  example, it is semantically identical. Each instance of the namespace =
name=20
  "bar" is replaced with "<A=20
  href=3D"http://www.del.jensen.org/">http://www.del.jensen.org/</A>" =
and then=20
  appended to the local name for each element tag. The resulting tag =
names in=20
  this example are exactly the same as for the previous example.=20
  <P><PRE>   &lt;foo:r xmlns:foo=3D"<A =
href=3D"http://www.del.jensen.org/glide">http://www.del.jensen.org/glide<=
/A>"&gt;
     &lt;foo:rname&gt;
          Johnny Updraft
     &lt;/foo:rname&gt;
     &lt;foo:raccidents/&gt;
   &lt;/foo:r&gt;
</PRE>
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-93>Page 93</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>This example is semantically identical to the two previous ones. =
Each=20
  instance of the namespace name "foo" is replaced with "<A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.del.jensen.org/glide">http://www.del.jensen.org/glide<=
/A>"=20
  which is then appended to the local name for each element tag, the =
resulting=20
  tag names are identical to those in the previous examples.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
